                <div class="main-content" >
                    
                        <section data-title="Introduction"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec1-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec1">Introduction</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec1-content"><p>The global push toward electrification and substantial greenhouse gas emission reductions is intensifying the need for sustainable technological solutions across the automotive sector and other energy-intensive industries. In this context, energy storage plays a pivotal role, serving as a critical enabler for low-carbon transportation, renewable energy integration, and grid resilience. The rapidly increasing demand for high-performance, scalable, and environmentally sustainable energy storage systems underscores the urgency of selecting appropriate battery technologies. This requires careful consideration of battery chemistries that can satisfy both short-term performance targets and long-term resource, cost, and sustainability constraints.</p><p>At present, lithium-ion batteries (LIBs) dominate the energy storage market, with cell costs averaging approximately €110/kWh<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Manzini, A., Martinez García, L. &amp; Harrivaara, P. Adoption of next-generation batteries: a survey-based analysis of user and expert perspectives. Min. Econ. 39, 71–91 (2025)." href="#ref-CR1" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e517">1</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Battery Report. (Volta Foundation, 2023)." href="#ref-CR2" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e517_1">2</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 3" title="Battery Report. (Volta Foundation, 2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR3" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e520">3</a></sup>. However, the pricing of LIBs remains highly sensitive to fluctuations in the cost of critical raw materials such as nickel, cobalt, and lithium, which have experienced significant volatility, reaching a peak in 2022 followed by a notable decline in 2024<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 4" title="Jones, B., Nguyen-Tien, V. &amp; Elliott, R. J. The electric vehicle revolution: Critical material supply chains, trade and development.  World Econ. 46, 2–26 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR4" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e524">4</a></sup>. While recent reductions in raw material prices have temporarily eased cost pressures, this downward trend is not expected to be sustainable. Upstream supply chains are facing increasing strain, and projections indicate that future mineral demand will substantially exceed historical levels<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 5" title="Global Critical Minerals Outlook 2025. (IEA, 2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR5" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e528">5</a></sup>. Achieving global decarbonization targets will require a sharp rise in the production of key metals such as cobalt, copper, tin, and zinc. However, expanding supply is hindered by long project lead times, declining ore grades, and increasing geopolitical and environmental constraints<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 5" title="Global Critical Minerals Outlook 2025. (IEA, 2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR5" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e532">5</a></sup>. Establishing a stable and equitable pricing environment that ensures upstream viability while maintaining downstream affordability is therefore essential to support the continued growth and sustainability of LIB technologies. At the same time, these structural limitations highlight the urgent need to diversify battery chemistries by exploring alternative systems based on more earth-abundant, geopolitically secure, and cost-effective materials to enhance the long-term resilience and scalability of energy storage infrastructure.</p><p>Battery manufacturers and end users must remain agile in adapting to rapidly evolving technologies, supply chain limitations, and shifting market dynamics<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 1" title="Manzini, A., Martinez García, L. &amp; Harrivaara, P. Adoption of next-generation batteries: a survey-based analysis of user and expert perspectives. Min. Econ. 39, 71–91 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR1" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e539">1</a></sup>. Battery cost continues to be a critical determinant of the competitiveness and scalability of energy storage systems. Affordable electric vehicles (EVs) offering long range, rapid charging, and robust safety, along with cost-effective, large-scale energy storage systems for renewable integration and grid stabilization, are essential to enabling the widespread adoption of sustainable mobility and a decarbonized electric energy infrastructure. Given the strong coupling between system-level economics, battery longevity, and material cost, advancing beyond current lithium-ion technologies has become increasingly urgent. In this scenario, the development of next-generation batteries utilizing earth-abundant, responsibly sourced materials offers a strategic path to reduce reliance on critical raw materials, improve supply chain resilience, and support the sustainable deployment of both mobile and stationary storage systems.</p><p>In this context, batteries employing sulfur cathodes have emerged as highly attractive candidates for next-generation energy storage systems. Sulfur is abundant, low-cost, and environmentally benign. Furthermore, sulfur-based conversion cathodes exhibit exceptionally high theoretical specific capacities and energy densities. Their low material cost and scalability also position them as strong candidates for stationary applications, including renewable energy integration and grid stabilization. By addressing both resource constraints and performance demands, sulfur cathode technologies represent a compelling route toward more sustainable, cost-effective, and geopolitically secure battery chemistries. To fully realize their potential, however, sulfur-based batteries (SBBs) must be developed through sustainable manufacturing approaches, prioritizing low toxicity, high recyclability, and circular economy principles. Incorporating life cycle assessments (LCA) and ensuring social and environmental responsibility across the value chain will be essential to enabling their responsible deployment and accelerating the transition to a cleaner and more resilient energy system.</p><p>This review provides a critical assessment of the development landscape for sulfur cathodes across various SBB chemistries, structured from the perspective of end-user performance requirements. Rather than organizing the discussion around conventional research-focused topics such as the shuttle effect or reaction kinetics, this review focuses on key application-driven performance metrics, including self-discharge, charge and discharge rate, durability, safety, energy density, and cost, that directly determine the practical viability of SBBs in real-world use cases. It highlights recent proposals in materials design and cell engineering aimed at enhancing performance, cycle life, and safety. In addition, the review outlines key challenges and strategic opportunities that could enable the transition from laboratory-scale research to commercially viable solutions. Following this introduction, the second section presents an overview of the advantages and inherent limitations of SBBs. The third section discusses technological approaches and existing barriers to advancing SBB systems. The fourth section explores scale-up considerations and outlines pathways toward commercialization, highlighting current worldwide initiatives. The review concludes by synthesizing the current state of the field and outlining critical next steps toward real-world implementation.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Advantages and limitations of sulfur cathodes"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec2-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec2">Advantages and limitations of sulfur cathodes</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec2-content"><p>Sulfur cathodes operate based on the redox chemistry of elemental sulfur in reaction with metal ions supplied by the anode (Fig.&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig1">1</a>). During discharge, sulfur, typically in the form of cyclic S₈ molecules, reacts with the metal ions in solution and is progressively reduced to sulfide ions (S²⁻) through a series of intermediate polysulfide species (e.g., S₈²⁻, S₆²⁻, S₄²⁻), while metal ions are simultaneously released from the anode. These metal ions may originate from metal stripping in the case of a metallic anode (e.g., Li, Na, Zn), deintercalation from intercalation-type anodes (e.g., graphite, hard carbon), or conversion reactions involving materials such as silicon. Upon charging, the process is reversed: S²⁻ is oxidized back to elemental sulfur, and metal ions are either electrodeposited onto the anode or reincorporated into the host material through intercalation or conversion mechanisms.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-1" data-title="SBB scheme."><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig1" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 1: SBB scheme.</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig1_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-1-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-1-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig1_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 1: SBB scheme." loading="lazy" width="685" height="330"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-1-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/1" data-track-dest="link:Figure1 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 1" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-1-desc"><p>Working principle of an SBB during charging (left) and discharging (right).</p></div></div></figure></div><p>Due to the inherently low electrical conductivity of elemental sulfur and its discharge products, typically metal sulfides (M<sub>y</sub>S), sulfur is commonly combined with a conductive host material to form a composite cathode. This host is usually a porous, carbon-based matrix that facilitates electron transport, enhances active material utilization, and accommodates volume changes during cycling.</p><p>Sulfur cathodes have attracted considerable interest in recent years due to their exceptional potential to exceed the energy density of conventional intercalation-type cathodes such as NMC (LiNiMnCoO₂), NCA (LiNiCoAlO₂), LMO (LiMn₂O₄), LCO (LiCoO<sub>2</sub>), and LFP (LiFePO₄), widely used in LIBs. The low atomic mass of sulfur, coupled with its ability to undergo a two-electron redox process (S₈ +16e-↔8S²⁻), enables a high theoretical specific capacity of 1675 mAh/g and a gravimetric energy density approaching 2600 Wh/kg, nearly five times that of typical LIB cathodes. These characteristics make sulfur a highly attractive candidate for applications that demand lightweight, high-energy storage solutions, including EVs, aerospace technologies, and portable electronics, where energy-to-weight ratios are crucial.</p><p>Beyond energy density, sulfur cathodes offer key advantages in terms of elemental abundance and cost-effectiveness. Sulfur is plentiful, non-toxic, and inexpensive, especially when compared to critical and supply-risk materials such as cobalt and nickel, which dominate many current LIB chemistries. Furthermore, sulfur cathodes are often composed of additional low-cost and potentially sustainable components, including porous carbon matrices, possibly derived from biomass, and, in some configurations, minimal amounts of transition metal catalysts to facilitate redox kinetics. The low cost and widespread availability of materials also make sulfur cathodes a highly attractive candidate for stationary and large-scale energy storage systems, both front-of-the-meter and behind-the-meter, aimed at supporting renewable energy integration and grid stabilization.</p><p>Importantly, the reduced dependence on critical raw materials enhances not only the economic attractiveness of sulfur-based systems but also their geopolitical and environmental sustainability. This positions sulfur cathodes as a strategic alternative for diversifying the battery material supply chain, reducing reliance on high-risk elements, and aligning battery development with broader circular economy and decarbonization objectives.</p><p>Despite these promising features, the large-scale commercialization of SBBs faces several technical and practical challenges, in part rooted in the intrinsic characteristics of sulfur redox chemistry (Fig.&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig2">2</a>), including:</p><ul class="u-list-style-bullet">
                <li>
                  <p>Low charge/discharge rates and related power density, with moderately long response times, stemming from sluggish redox kinetics between sulfur and metal ions, as well as limited electronic and ionic transport within the cathode and electrolyte.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Moderate round-trip energy efficiency, due to significant overpotentials required to drive redox reactions.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Low practical energy densities, constrained by limited sulfur loading, incomplete M-S reaction, and the use of excess electrolyte in current designs priorizing cycling stability.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Limited cycling stability, driven by active material loss at the cathode and the degradation of both the anode and electrolyte.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Limited operation temperature range with stability problems at high temperatures and poor low-temperature performance.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>High self-discharge rates and resting capacity fade, largely attributed to the migration of intermediate polysulfides.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Poor thermal dissipation, both internal and external, resulting from the inherently low thermal conductivity of porous sulfur-based cathodes.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Safety concerns mainly related to the use of toxic and highly volatile electrolytes and lithium or other metal anodes, which are commonly employed to match the high capacity of the sulfur cathode.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Limitations with current battery infrastructure and high manufacturing costs stemming from the use of lithium metal anodes and flammable ether-based solvents, the associated requirement for stringent processing conditions, and the lack of an established supply chain.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Environmental and recycling challenges, emphasizing the need for sustainable and cost-effective end-of-life strategies.</p>
                </li>
              </ul><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-2" data-title="Key limitations in SBBs."><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig2" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 2: Key limitations in SBBs.</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig2_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-2-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-2-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig2_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 2: Key limitations in SBBs." loading="lazy" width="685" height="590"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-2-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/2" data-track-dest="link:Figure2 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 2" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-2-desc"><p>Overview of the key limitations in SBBs and the underlying mechanisms responsible for these challenges.</p></div></div></figure></div><p>Table&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Tab1">1</a> provides a comparison of performance metrics for current SBBs, primarily lithium-sulfur batteries (LSBs) utilizing lithium metal anodes, and commercial LIBs, benchmarked against target values for EVs and stationary energy storage systems. The table highlights the likelihood of each metric being achieved by a properly designed SBB. It is important to note that achieving certain performance targets may require departing from conventional cell configurations. For instance, attaining higher operating voltages may necessitate alternative architectures such as bipolar designs (not considered in the table), while addressing safety concerns could involve moving away from lithium metal anodes. Although most individual targets are achievable in isolation, meeting them simultaneously presents a huge technological challenge.</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-1"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab1" data-test="table-caption">Table 1 Comparison of current laboratory LSB and commercial LIB performance metrics against target values for EVs and stationary energy storage systems<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="BloombergNEF. Lithium-Ion Battery Pack Prices See Largest Drop Since 2017, Falling to $115 per Kilowatt-Hour: BloombergNEF, 
                  https://about.bnef.com/insights/commodities/lithium-ion-battery-pack-prices-see-largest-drop-since-2017-falling-to-115-per-kilowatt-hour-bloombergnef/
                  
                 (2024)." href="#ref-CR219" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e701">219</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="(DOE)., U. D. o. E. FOTW #1354, August 5, 2024: Electric Vehicle Battery Pack Costs for a Light-Duty Vehicle in 2023 Are 90% Lower than in 2008, according to DOE Estimates, 
                  https://www.energy.gov/eere/vehicles/articles/fotw-1354-august-5-2024-electric-vehicle-battery-pack-costs-light-duty
                  
                 (2024)." href="#ref-CR220" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e701_1">220</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Enevate. Enevate Achieves Major Goals in 2021, Ramping its Pioneering Battery Technology to Address Global Electric Vehicle (EV) Battery Demand, 
                  https://www.enevate.com/enevate-achieves-major-ev-battery-technology-goals-in-2021/
                  
                 (2021)." href="#ref-CR221" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e701_2">221</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="COMMISSION, E. SET-Plan ACTION n°7 –Declaration of Intent “Become competitive in the global battery sector to drive e-mobility forward”, 
                  https://setis.ec.europa.eu/system/files/2021-05/action7_declaration_of_intent_0.pdf
                  
                 (2016)." href="#ref-CR222" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e701_3">222</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Wesley Cole, V. R., and Merve Turan. Cost Projections for Utility-Scale Battery Storage: 2025 Update. (National Renewable Energy Laboratory, 2025)." href="#ref-CR223" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e701_4">223</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 224" title="IRENA. Electricity Storage Valuation Framework: Assessing system value and ensuring project viability. (International Renewable Energy Agency, Abu Dhabi, 2020)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR224" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e704">224</a></sup></b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/tables/1" aria-label="Full size table 1"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p>A major limitation in the current SBB research landscape is the widespread use of idealized, non-representative testing conditions. Many laboratory studies and literature reports rely on low sulfur loadings (<span class="stix">∼</span>1 mg/cm<sup>2</sup>), electrolyte-rich environments (E/S &gt; 20 µL/mg<sup>1</sup>), and thick lithium foils (&gt;100 µm). While valuable for fundamental analysis, these conditions obscure the practical challenges faced in commercial cells and often lead to an overestimation of key performance metrics, such as cycle life.</p><p>Consequently, when moving to practical assembly conditions, a substantial drop in electrochemical performance is expected. Under realistic cathode loadings (<span class="stix">∼</span>4–6 mg/cm<sup>2</sup>), achievable capacity typically falls to 400–600 mAh/g<sup>1</sup>, and cycle life may reach only 200–500 cycles, which is well below the 1000–1500 cycles frequently reported under optimized lab conditions. Practical factors such as ambient temperature, dynamic current profiles, and industrial‑grade cell components further reduce performance, lowering Coulombic efficiency and increasing self‑discharge, especially at high rates and lean electrolyte. These realistic estimates better reflect the current technology’s true limitations and highlight the critical need for research under commercially relevant conditions. To better gauge real-world viability, the field must adopt transparent reporting and realistic testing benchmarks, targeting areal capacities &gt;5 mAh/cm<sup>2</sup>, sulfur loadings &gt;5 mg/cm<sup>2</sup>, lean electrolyte conditions (E/S &lt; 5 µL/mg<sup>1</sup>), and limited lithium excess. Encouragingly, advances in porous carbon frameworks, 2D materials, catalytic additives, and interfacial coatings are already demonstrating promising pathways to bridge this gap and enable high-performance, practical SBB systems<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Zhao, M., Li, B.-Q., Zhang, X.-Q., Huang, J.-Q. &amp; Zhang, Q. A perspective toward practical lithium–sulfur batteries. ACS Cent. Sci. 6, 1095–1104 (2020)." href="#ref-CR6" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e741">6</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Chung, S. H. &amp; Manthiram, A. Current status and future prospects of metal–sulfur batteries. Adv. Mater. 31, 1901125 (2019)." href="#ref-CR7" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e741_1">7</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Yao, W., Liao, K., Lai, T., Sul, H. &amp; Manthiram, A. Rechargeable metal-sulfur batteries: key materials to mechanisms. Chem. Rev. 124, 4935–5118 (2024)." href="#ref-CR8" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e741_2">8</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Hwang, J.-Y., Park, H., Kim, H., Kansara, S. &amp; Sun, Y.-K. Advanced Cathodes for Practical Lithium–Sulfur Batteries. Acc. Mater. Res. 6, 245–258 (2025)." href="#ref-CR9" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e741_3">9</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 10" title="Wu, C.-C., Chan, T.-C. &amp; Chung, S.-H. Progress on critical cell fabrication parameters and designs for advanced lithium–sulfur batteries. Chem. Commun. 60, 11017–11033 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR10" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e744">10</a></sup>.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Technological means and limits to overcome sulfur cathode challenges"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec3-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec3">Technological means and limits to overcome sulfur cathode challenges</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec3-content"><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec4">Low charge/discharge rates and relatively long response times</h3><p>The rate performance of SBBs, like other conversion-type systems, is typically constrained to <span class="stix">∼</span>1 C, corresponding to <span class="stix">∼</span>1 A/g<sub>s</sub> for standard lab-scale carbon-sulfur cathodes with low sulfur loadings (e.g., 1 mg/cm², yielding <span class="stix">∼</span>1 mAh/cm² areal capacity). Beyond this rate, capacity losses exceeding 50% are common, with near-total capacity fade observed at 3 C–5 C. These limitations become even more critical in the high-loading cathodes required for practical applications, where charge transport and reaction kinetics impose stronger constraints<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 6" title="Zhao, M., Li, B.-Q., Zhang, X.-Q., Huang, J.-Q. &amp; Zhang, Q. A perspective toward practical lithium–sulfur batteries. ACS Cent. Sci. 6, 1095–1104 (2020)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR6" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e762">6</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 9" title="Hwang, J.-Y., Park, H., Kim, H., Kansara, S. &amp; Sun, Y.-K. Advanced Cathodes for Practical Lithium–Sulfur Batteries. Acc. Mater. Res. 6, 245–258 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR9" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e765">9</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Zhao, F. et al. Toward high-sulfur-content, high-performance lithium-sulfur batteries: Review of materials and technologies. J. Energy Chem. 80, 625–657 (2023)." href="#ref-CR11" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e768">11</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Wang, T. et al. Strategies toward high-loading lithium–sulfur batteries. ACS Energy Lett. 8, 116–150 (2022)." href="#ref-CR12" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e768_1">12</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Heo, J. et al. Recent advances in achieving high energy/power density of lithium–sulfur batteries for current and near-future applications. Battery Energy 4, e20240051 (2025)." href="#ref-CR13" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e768_2">13</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Yu, J. et al. Mechanistic insights and technical challenges in sulfur-based batteries: a comprehensive in situ/operando monitoring toolbox. ACS Energy Lett. 9, 6178–6214 (2024)." href="#ref-CR14" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e768_3">14</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 15" title="Chung, S.-H. &amp; Manthiram, A. Designing lithium-sulfur cells with practically necessary parameters. Joule 2, 710–724 (2018)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR15" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e771">15</a></sup>.</p><p>The low achievable charge and discharge rates in SBBs directly constrain both rapid charging capability and sustained power output, rendering current systems unsuitable for the demanding performance requirements of EVs. Moreover, the inherently low discharge rates of sulfur cathodes ultimately also limit the response time of SBBs, which a priori have no other intrinsic barrier delaying the onset of sulfur redox reactions, such as the need for external heating or mechanical activation. A slow response hinders deployment in critical applications such as grid stabilization during power outages, where both high-rate performance and rapid activation are essential.</p><p>The limited rate performance of SBBs stems from sluggish electrochemical kinetics combined with charge and mass transport limitations, leading to relatively high internal impedances. While typical NMC/graphite LIBs show impedances in the range of 50–100 Ω cm², LSBs often present much higher values, especially during cycling and in high-sulfur-loading configurations, ranging from 200 to 500 Ω cm², and in some cases exceeding 1000 Ω cm²<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 16" title="Huang, Y. C., Wu, C. C. &amp; Chung, S. H. Enhanced performance of lithium-sulfur batteries using construction wastes: a sustainable approach to high-loading sulfur cathodes. ChemSusChem 18, e202402206 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR16" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e781">16</a></sup>.</p><p>Several factors contribute to the elevated impedance that underlies the low charge/discharge rates and sluggish response times of SBBs. First, both elemental sulfur and the fully discharged metal sulfide are electrically insulating, resulting in the formation of resistive layers on the cathode during both charge and discharge, which severely restricts electron and ion transport. Additionally, the M-S conversion reaction involves a multi-step redox process with several intermediate polysulfides whose successive formation and transformation are kinetically hindered, leading to high charge transfer resistance and significant overpotentials, effects that become more pronounced at higher current densities. Furthermore, the dissolution and sluggish diffusion of polysulfide species in conventional electrolytes diminish the availability of active material at the electrode surface, thereby impairing the rate capability. In addition, the presence of dissolved polysulfides lowers the ionic mobility of the electrolyte, further contributing to increased cell resistance. These combined limitations hinder the fast electrochemical kinetics necessary for rapid charging and discharging, while also contributing to thermal buildup during operation. Therefore, mitigating the high impedance stemming from poor electronic and ionic conductivity and sluggish sulfur redox kinetics is critical to enabling high-rate operation in SBBs without inducing excessive heat generation.</p><p>To address the sluggish kinetics of sulfur redox reactions, electrocatalytic additives can be incorporated into the cathode composite. The addition of small amounts of metal-based catalysts has been shown to significantly enhance rate performance, maintaining up to 50% of the capacity even at high charge/discharge rates of 5 C, with minimal impact on the overall weight and energy density<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Jia, Y. et al. Variable and intelligent catalyst design based on local chemical environments in sulfur redox reactions. Joule 9, 101878 (2025)." href="#ref-CR17" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e792">17</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Yu, J. et al. Promoting polysulfide redox reactions through electronic spin manipulation. ACS Nano 18, 19268–19282 (2024)." href="#ref-CR18" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e792_1">18</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 19" title="Li, C. et al. Balancing electronic spin state via atomically-dispersed heteronuclear Fe–Co pairs for high-performance sodium–sulfur batteries. J. Am. Chem. Soc. 147, 8250–8259 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR19" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e795">19</a></sup>. However, integrating catalysts into the cathode increases system complexity, introducing challenges related to electrode fabrication and cathode architecture optimization. As a simplified alternative, catalysts can be applied to the cathode-facing side of the separator, a configuration that lowers fabrication complexity and cost while still promoting the catalytic conversion of polysulfides<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 20" title="Li, C. et al. Tungsten phosphide on nitrogen and phosphorus-doped carbon as a functional membrane coating enabling robust lithium-sulfur batteries. J. Colloid Interface Sci. 670, 61–72 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR20" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e799">20</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 21" title="Li, C. et al. Three Birds with One Stone: Multifunctional Separators Based on SnSe Nanosheets Enable High-Performance Li-, Na-and K-Sulfur Batteries. Adv. Energy Mater. 14, 2303551 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR21" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e802">21</a></sup>. Nevertheless, the effectiveness of this approach under practical high sulfur loading and lean electrolyte formulations remains an open question.</p><p>Just as critical as improving the kinetics of the sulfur redox reactions is enhancing both electronic and ionic conductivity within the cathode. Achieving this improved transport requires fine cathode design and engineering using highly conductive materials, such as carbon scaffolds, including hierarchical porous carbon networks or hybrid architectures, that enable efficient electron transport and metal-ion diffusion<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 22" title="Li, F. et al. Enhancing lithium–sulfur battery performance with MXene: specialized structures and innovative designs. Adv. Sci. 11, 2404328 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR22" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e809">22</a></sup>. Polar and surface functionalized materials that combine high conductivity with strong polysulfide anchoring capability are particularly advantageous. An alternative approach involves incorporating metal sulfides as the sulfur source to improve the electrical conductivity of both charged and discharged states<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 23" title="Wu, C.-C., Chan, T.-C. &amp; Chung, S.-H. Metal-based composite sulfur cathodes for lithium–sulfur electrochemical cells. Commun. Mater. 6, 111 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR23" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e813">23</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 24" title="Šutka, A., Timusk, M., Loot, A., Joost, U. &amp; Käämbre, T. Polarizable nanowire colloids for power free naked eye optical detection of electrostatic surface charges. Adv. Mater. Technol. 1, 1600154 (2016)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR24" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e816">24</a></sup>. However, these materials often introduce significant additional weight, which can compromise the overall energy density of the cell. Thus, their inclusion must be carefully optimized to balance conductivity enhancement with energy storage efficiency.</p><p>To address the limitations imposed by polysulfide availability on reaction kinetics, various strategies have been developed. One common approach involves suppressing polysulfide dissolution by using solid-state electrolytes (SSEs) or liquid electrolytes incapable of solvating polysulfides<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Li, H. et al. Kinetically-enhanced gradient modulator layer enables wide-temperature ultralong-life all-solid-state lithium-sulfur batteries. Adv. Energy Mater. 15, 2501259 (2025)." href="#ref-CR25" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e823">25</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Ji, Y. et al. PIM-1 as a multifunctional framework to enable high-performance solid-state lithium–sulfur batteries. Adv. Funct. Mater. 31, 2104830 (2021)." href="#ref-CR26" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e823_1">26</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Weller, C., Thieme, S., Härtel, P., Althues, H. &amp; Kaskel, S. Intrinsic shuttle suppression in lithium-sulfur batteries for pouch cell application. J. Electrochem. Soc. 164, A3766 (2017)." href="#ref-CR27" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e823_2">27</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 28" title="Liu, Y. et al. Electrolyte solutions design for lithium-sulfur batteries. Joule 5, 2323–2364 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR28" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e826">28</a></sup>. While effective in confining sulfur species, this suppression often introduces a critical trade-off: it can lead to a reduced voltage in the first discharge plateau, lower overall capacity, and, most counterproductively, slower reaction kinetics<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 29" title="Senol Gungor, A. et al. Understanding Rate and Capacity Limitations in Li–S Batteries Based on Solid-State Sulfur Conversion in Confinement. ACS Appl. Mater. interfaces 16, 67651–67661 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR29" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e830">29</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 30" title="Kim, S. C. et al. Solvation-property relationship of lithium-sulphur battery electrolytes. Nat. Commun. 15, 1268 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR30" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e833">30</a></sup>. These drawbacks arise from the dominance of solid-solid conversion reactions, which are inherently sluggish due to limited ionic conductivity/diffusivity. Moreover, the effectiveness of catalytic additives in such systems may be significantly diminished, particularly under high sulfur loading, owing to the reduced interface area among the catalyst, sulfur, metal ions, and conductive carbon.</p><p>Alternatively, polysulfide species can be spatially confined near the reaction interface through the use of trapping layers positioned at the cathode-electrolyte interface or on the separator<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 31" title="Qin, B. et al. Ultra-lightweight ion-sieving membranes for high-rate lithium sulfur batteries. Chem. Eng. J. 430, 132698 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR31" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e840">31</a></sup>. These layers limit polysulfide migration while preserving a locally high concentration, sustaining redox activity, and improving cycling stability. Another strategy involves confining sulfur within nano- or microporous structures, which shortens diffusion pathways and enhances surface reactivity, thereby improving reaction kinetics<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 32" title="Saroha, R. et al. Self-supported hierarchically porous 3D carbon nanofiber network comprising Ni/Co/NiCo2O4 nanocrystals and hollow N-doped C nanocages as sulfur host for highly reversible Li–S batteries. Chem. Eng. J. 446, 137141 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR32" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e844">32</a></sup>. However, this approach is limited by the relatively low sulfur loading typically achievable in nano/microporous carbon hosts, which compromises energy density. Moreover, strong confinement can shift the electrochemical pathway toward less efficient solid-solid conversions.</p><p>At the current collector level, the use of three-dimensional (3D) architectures can significantly enhance both electrical conductivity and metal-ion accessibility, particularly in thick high-sulfur-loading cathodes<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 33" title="Papandrea, B. et al. Three-dimensional graphene framework with ultra-high sulfur content for a robust lithium–sulfur battery. Nano Res. 9, 240–248 (2016)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR33" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e851">33</a></sup>. By increasing the interfacial contact area between the cathode and the current collector, 3D structures facilitate more uniform charge distribution and reduce local current density, thereby improving overall electrochemical performance. Additionally, their interconnected porous frameworks can provide efficient ion transport pathways and mechanical support for high-sulfur-loading electrodes, contributing to better rate capability and cycling stability.</p><p>At the electrolyte level, the development of low-viscosity, high-conductivity formulations is essential to enable fast metal-ion transport and support high-rate operation<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 34" title="Le Mong, A., Ahn, Y., Puttaswamy, R. &amp; Kim, D. Pore filled solid electrolytes with high ionic conduction and electrochemical stability for lithium sulfur battery. Energy Mater. 3, 10.20517 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR34" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e858">34</a></sup>. Besides, beyond improving bulk transport properties, the inclusion of redox mediators has emerged as a promising strategy to accelerate the conversion of long-chain polysulfides<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 35" title="Zhao, C. X. et al. Redox mediator assists electron transfer in lithium–sulfur batteries with sulfurized polyacrylonitrile cathodes. EcoMat 3, e12066 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR35" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e862">35</a></sup>. These mediators act as soluble electron shuttles, promoting rapid and reversible redox reactions and effectively bypassing the sluggish kinetics of direct electrochemical pathways, thereby enhancing overall reaction efficiency and rate performance. However, these redox mediators may be incompatible with the limited electrolyte volumes permitted in high-energy-density cells.</p><p>Recent studies have also shown that external magnetic fields can enhance polysulfide conversion kinetics and facilitate gas bubble detachment from the electrode surface, thereby improving mass transport and overall reaction rates<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Zhang, C. Y. et al. Spin effect to promote reaction kinetics and overall performance of lithium-sulfur batteries under external magnetic field. Angew. Chem. Int. Ed. 61, e202211570 (2022)." href="#ref-CR36" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e870">36</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Zhang, C. Y. et al. Sodium-sulfur batteries with unprecedented capacity, cycling stability and operation temperature range enabled by a CoFe2O4 catalytic additive under an external magnetic field. Adv. Funct. Mater. 33, 2305908 (2023)." href="#ref-CR37" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e870_1">37</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 38" title="Zhang, C. Y. et al. Spin-modulated catalysis in sulfur cathodes for improved performance in lithium–sulfur batteries. Commun. Mater. 6, 256 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR38" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e873">38</a></sup>. However, such strategies require additional external hardware, which increases system complexity, weight, size, and cost. Unless these mechanisms can be integrated with minimal added weight and volume at the cell, module, or battery-pack level, their practical viability remains limited.</p><p>In a similar direction, thermal management at the cell or system level, using Joule heating techniques to elevate the temperature of the cathode, individual cell, or entire battery pack, can accelerate sulfur redox kinetics. A notable example is the case of high-temperature sodium-sulfur (Na-S) batteries, which operate using molten sulfur and sodium and are already commercially deployed<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 39" title="Nikiforidis, G., Van de Sanden, M. &amp; Tsampas, M. N. High and intermediate temperature sodium–sulfur batteries for energy storage: development, challenges and perspectives. RSC Adv. 9, 5649–5673 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR39" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e880">39</a></sup>. Nevertheless, these systems typically function at modest charge/discharge rates (C/5 to C/3), highlighting the intrinsic challenge of achieving high-rate performance in SBBs, even under favorable liquid-phase conditions.</p><p>Beyond thermal strategies, artificial intelligence (AI)-enabled battery management systems (BMS) are being developed in LIBs to dynamically optimize charging protocols in real time, balancing fast charging with long-term battery health<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 40" title="Omojola, A. F. et al. Artificial intelligence-driven strategies for advancing lithium-ion battery performance and safety. Int. J. Adv. Eng. Manag. 6, 452–484 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR40" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e887">40</a></sup>. Similar approaches need to be extended to sulfur-based systems, potentially improving performance under variable operating conditions.</p><p>Finally, efficient heat dissipation is critical during fast charging. However, as discussed in “Poor thermal dissipation”, this remains a key limitation in SBBs, further constraining their high-rate capabilities. Figure&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig3">3</a> displays an overview of the factors limiting SBB rate performance and some of the proposed strategies to overcome this limitation.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-3" data-title="Mechanisms limiting rate performance."><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig3" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 3: Mechanisms limiting rate performance.</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig3_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-3-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-3-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig3_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 3: Mechanisms limiting rate performance." loading="lazy" width="685" height="821"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-3-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/3" data-track-dest="link:Figure3 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 3" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-3-desc"><p>Schematic illustration of the key mechanisms limiting the rate performance of SBBs and the strategies proposed to address them.</p></div></div></figure></div><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec5">Moderate round-trip energy efficiency</h3><p>The round-trip energy efficiency of SBBs typically ranges between 70–85%, which is considerably lower than that of conventional LIBs. This limitation is primarily attributed to the difference between charge and discharge voltages, which averages around 10% of the discharge potential at low current rates, intrinsically capping the round-trip energy efficiency by the same margin (Fig.&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig4">4</a>). At higher current densities, this hysteresis becomes more pronounced, further reducing the energy efficiency of the system. This voltage difference is directly related to the overpotential required to drive the sluggish multi-step sulfur redox reaction (S₈↔Li₂S).</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-4" data-title="Charging and discharging curves."><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig4" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 4: Charging and discharging curves.</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig4_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-4-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-4-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig4_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 4: Charging and discharging curves." loading="lazy" width="685" height="693"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-4-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/4" data-track-dest="link:Figure4 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 4" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-4-desc"><p>Representative galvanostatic charge (red) and discharge (blue) curves of a conventional LSB based on an ether electrolyte, highlighting the key electrochemical reactions at each stage and the voltage gap between charge and discharge<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 218" title="Yu, J. et al. Promoting electrochemical reactions with dual-atom catalysts for high-rate lithium–sulfur batteries. Adv. Mater. e11345 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR218" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e939">218</a></sup>.</p></div></div></figure></div><p>Improving this situation demands the development of high-performance electrocatalysts to reduce the energy barriers associated with the sulfur redox processes<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 41" title="Lian, Z. et al. Accelerating sulfur redox kinetics by rare earth single-atom electrocatalysts toward efficient lithium–sulfur batteries. Appl. Catal. B: Environ. Energy 361, 124661 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR41" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e954">41</a></sup>. Beyond catalytic improvements, the incorporation of redox mediators has shown potential for enhancing reaction kinetics by facilitating electron transfer through lower-energy shuttle mechanisms<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 42" title="Tsao, Y. et al. Designing a quinone-based redox mediator to facilitate Li2S oxidation in Li-S batteries. Joule 3, 872–884 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR42" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e958">42</a></sup>. However, these mediators must be carefully chosen and confined to the cathode side to avoid additional overpotentials and parasitic redox reactions that can offset their benefits.</p><p>An additional limiting factor is the inherently insulating nature of both the charged and discharged products, S₈ and M<sub>y</sub>S, which introduces additional significant impedance in the system. This can be addressed by designing highly conductive hierarchical cathode frameworks<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 22" title="Li, F. et al. Enhancing lithium–sulfur battery performance with MXene: specialized structures and innovative designs. Adv. Sci. 11, 2404328 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR22" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e967">22</a></sup> incorporating porous carbon networks<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 43" title="Chen, P.-Y., Cho, C.-S. &amp; Li, C.-C. Enhancing performance of lithium-sulfur batteries through porous carbon network integration in carbonized cotton. Mater. Res. Bull. 170, 112563 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR43" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e971">43</a></sup>. Besides, enhancing the ionic conductivity of electrolytes<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 44" title="Cui, X., Wang, X. &amp; Pan, Q. Achieving fast and stable Li+ transport in lithium-sulfur battery via a high ionic conduction and high adhesion solid polymer electrolyte. Energy Mater. 3, 20517 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR44" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e975">44</a></sup> and reducing their viscosity<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 45" title="Wu, F. et al. Boosting high-performance in lithium–sulfur batteries via dilute electrolyte. Nano Lett. 20, 5391–5399 (2020)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR45" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e979">45</a></sup> is also critical to minimizing voltage drops.</p><p>The sharp increase in overpotential with rising charge/discharge rates, resulting in greater energy loss per cycle, is largely attributed to mass transport limitations at the electrode-electrolyte interface, which hinder the local supply of active reactants and impede reaction kinetics. One way to alleviate this issue is by suppressing polysulfide dissolution, thereby retaining active species near the reaction site. However, as noted above, this approach shifts the dominant mechanism toward solid-state charge transport through electronically and ionically insulating phases, which imposes an additional overpotential that is detrimental to the energy efficiency of the process.</p><p>Another contributor to energy loss is the shuttle effect, in which dissolved polysulfides migrate between the electrodes, leading to parasitic reactions at the lithium anode. This contributes to overall energy inefficiency by lowering the Coulombic efficiency. Suppressing this shuttle effect through the use of separator coatings<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 46" title="Ma, C. et al. Dual-engineered separator for highly robust, all-climate lithium-sulfur batteries. Energy Storage Mater. 32, 46–54 (2020)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR46" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e990">46</a></sup>, electrolyte additives<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Ovc-Okene, D., Shankar, L. S., Vizintin, A. &amp; Kun, R. Revitalizing Li–S batteries: the power of electrolyte additives. RSC Adv. 15, 5381–5404 (2025)." href="#ref-CR47" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e994">47</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Yang, J.-L., Yang, P., Cai, D.-Q., Wang, Z. &amp; Fan, H. J. Atomically dispersed Fe-N4 and Ni-N4 independent sites enable bidirectional sulfur redox electrocatalysis. Nano Lett. 23, 4000–4007 (2023)." href="#ref-CR48" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e994_1">48</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 49" title="Liu, M. et al. Dithiothreitol as a promising electrolyte additive to suppress the “shuttle effect” by slicing the disulfide bonds of polysulfides in lithium-sulfur batteries. J. Power Sources 424, 254–260 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR49" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e997">49</a></sup> or solid-state barriers<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 50" title="Yang, Q. et al. A review on 1D materials for all-solid-state lithium-ion batteries and all-solid-state lithium-sulfur batteries. Chem. Eng. J. 451, 138532 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR50" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1001">50</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 51" title="Umeshbabu, E., Zheng, B. &amp; Yang, Y. Recent progress in all-solid-state lithium-sulfur batteries using high Li-ion conductive solid electrolytes. Electrochem. Energy Rev. 2, 199–230 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR51" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1004">51</a></sup> is therefore essential for improving energy efficiency.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec6">Low practical energy densities</h3><p>SBBs, and LSBs in particular, offer exceptionally high theoretical energy densities. This advantage stems from the combination of a sulfur cathode, which possesses a high theoretical specific capacity of 1675 mAh/g, and a lithium metal anode, which delivers the highest known specific capacity among anode materials (3680 mAh/g). As a result, LSBs can theoretically achieve gravimetric energy densities exceeding 1000 Wh/ kg, significantly surpassing those of conventional LIBs, which are typically limited to around 500 Wh/kg.</p><p>In practice, however, the gravimetric energy density of LSBs falls far short of the theoretical maximum. Although record values of up to 700 Wh/kg have been reached at Tsinghua University and the Beijing Institute of Technology<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 52" title="Li, X.-Y. et al. Two-stage solvation of lithium polysulfides in working lithium–sulfur batteries. J. Am. Chem. Soc. 147, 15435–15447 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR52" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1019">52</a></sup>, these are typically achieved at the expense of limited cycle life. This performance gap stems primarily from three factors: low sulfur loadings, the need for excessive electrolyte volumes to prolong cycling, and inefficient sulfur utilization at higher loadings.</p><p>The redox chemistry of sulfur is inherently sluggish and involves insulating species such as elemental sulfur and Li₂S, which hinder both electronic and ionic transport. To counteract this, sulfur is typically embedded within conductive carbon matrices<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 53" title="Ji, X., Lee, K. T. &amp; Nazar, L. F. A highly ordered nanostructured carbon–sulphur cathode for lithium-sulphur batteries. Nat. Mater. 8, 500–506 (2009)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR53" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1026">53</a></sup> and often combined with catalytic additives to accelerate polysulfide conversion<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 54" title="Feng, Y. et al. Ultrahigh-Content Co-P cluster as a dual-atom-site electrocatalyst for accelerating polysulfides conversion in Li–S batteries. Adv. Funct. Mater. 32, 2207579 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR54" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1030">54</a></sup>. These components, while necessary for performance, dilute the active material content, reducing the actual sulfur fraction in the cathode to 70 wt% or less. On top of this, in laboratory-scale cells, sulfur loadings are often kept low (<span class="stix">∼</span>1 mg/cm²) to ensure full electrochemical utilization and minimize polarization.</p><p>Even under these conditions, the sulfur conversion reaction is often incomplete. This issue is especially pronounced in non-Li-based systems, where the lower reduction potential of the metal compared to lithium leads to even slower polysulfide conversion kinetics, ultimately reducing the achievable cell capacity.</p><p>Additionally, large volumes of electrolyte, frequently exceeding 20 µL per mg of sulfur, are used to promote sulfur dissolution, facilitate polysulfide transport, and compensate for lithium loss during cycling. These conditions, while suitable for demonstrating fundamental performance, are incompatible with commercial requirements, which call for high sulfur loadings (&gt;5 mg/cm²) and low electrolyte-to-sulfur (E/S) ratios (&lt;5 µL/mg) to reach energy densities compatible with LIBs<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 55" title="Chung, S.-H. &amp; Manthiram, A. Designing lithium–sulfur batteries with high-loading cathodes at a lean electrolyte condition. ACS Appl. Mater. Interfaces 10, 43749–43759 (2018)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR55" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1041">55</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 56" title="Fei, Y. &amp; Li, G. Unveiling the pivotal parameters for advancing high energy density in lithium-sulfur batteries: a comprehensive review. Adv. Funct. Mater. 34, 2312550 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR56" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1044">56</a></sup>.</p><p>Achieving energy densities that exceed those of LIBs, targeting up to 500 Wh/kg, demands not only very high sulfur loadings (&gt;10 mg/cm²) but also ultra-lean electrolyte conditions (E/S &lt; 2 µL/mg) and low negative-to-positive (N/P) capacity ratios (&lt;1.5). These aggressive cell configurations place tremendous stress on every component of the battery, exacerbating issues such as incomplete sulfur utilization, electrode passivation by Li₂S, and rapid capacity fading.</p><p>Replacing lithium metal with alternative anodes, using other metal-sulfur chemistries (e.g., Na-S, Mg-S), or moving to aqueous electrolytes to improve safety and reduce cost generally leads to lower achievable energy densities due to reduced anode capacity and/or higher molar mass.</p><p>Figure&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig5">5</a> displays the theoretical limit energy densities of various SBB systems, along with the corresponding weight fractions of each component in these optimized cell configurations. The calculations consider the specific discharge voltages, anode capacities, and cathode current collectors of each system and assume a sulfur loading of 15 mg/cm<sup>2</sup> with 80 wt% sulfur content in the cathode, a N/P capacity ratio of 1.2, and an E/S ratio of 1.2<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Fei, Y. &amp; Li, G. Unveiling the pivotal parameters for advancing high energy density in lithium-sulfur batteries: a comprehensive review. Adv. Funct. Mater. 34, 2312550 (2024)." href="#ref-CR56" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1062">56</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="McCloskey, B. D. Attainable gravimetric and volumetric energy density of Li–S and Li ion battery cells with solid separator-protected Li metal anodes.  J. Phys. Chem. Lett. 6, 4581–4588 (2015)." href="#ref-CR57" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1062_1">57</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 58" title="Zhou, G., Chen, H. &amp; Cui, Y. Formulating energy density for designing practical lithium–sulfur batteries. Nat. Energy 7, 312–319 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR58" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1065">58</a></sup>. For comparison, two representative LSB configurations commonly used in laboratory settings are included: a typical lab-scale LSB (LSB Lab), with a sulfur loading of 1 mg/cm², 60 wt% sulfur content, and E/S = 30; and a high-loading, lean-electrolyte LSB (LSB HL) with 5 mg/cm² sulfur loading, 70% sulfur content, and E/S = 7. Notably, even in the LSB HL case, the electrolyte weight fraction remains substantially higher than what is required to achieve energy densities comparable to state-of-the-art LIBs.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-5" data-title="Energy densities and component weight fractions."><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig5" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 5: Energy densities and component weight fractions.</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig5_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-5-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-5-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig5_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 5: Energy densities and component weight fractions." loading="lazy" width="685" height="478"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-5-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/5" data-track-dest="link:Figure5 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 5" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-5-desc"><p>Theoretical energy densities and component weight fractions in SBB systems operating at their maximum projected energy density. Parameters: sulfur loading 15 mg/cm<sup>2</sup>; 80 wt% cathode sulfur content; N/P = 1.2; and E/S = 1.2 as indicated at the top of each bar. The component weight fractions of conventional laboratory LSBs (LSB Lab) and conventional high-loading LSBs (LSB HL) are also included as reference. NaSB Na-S battery, ZnSB Zn-S battery, AlSB Al-S battery, MgSB Mg-S battery, FeSB Fe-S battery, GSB = LSB with a graphite anode, HCSB Na-S battery with a hard carbon anode.</p></div></div></figure></div><p>Meeting the stringent requirements for high energy density under realistic operating conditions remains one of the most difficult challenges in SBB development. Under lean-electrolyte and high-loading conditions, the performance of sulfur electrodes is increasingly limited by sluggish kinetics, insufficient conductivity, restricted mass transport, and electrode instability. A significant fraction of the sulfur may remain electrochemically inactive, and insulating Li₂S can rapidly passivate the active surfaces, degrading both capacity and rate capability. Particularly difficult is to reduce the electrolyte content as this needs to properly wet all the porous carbon and the separator, and eventually a porous anode, and it needs to provide sufficient room for the dissolution of the metal ion salts, additives, and potentially redox mediators and polysulfides near the cathode surface.</p><p>Overcoming these limitations requires advances in cell assembly/processing and the rational design of electrolytes, separators, and cathode architectures. In particular, practical wetting of thick, porous sulfur cathodes under lean-electrolyte conditions often benefits from dedicated manufacturing strategies. Vacuum-assisted electrolyte filling, already used in scaled pouch-cell production, helps evacuate trapped gas and drives electrolyte into deep pore networks, reducing dry regions that otherwise aggravate polarization and polysulfide shuttling. Wetting can be further improved through temperature-assisted filling (moderately elevated temperatures to reduce viscosity and enhance capillary penetration), often combined with controlled pressure or pressure-cycling protocols to promote infiltration in tortuous structures.</p><p>Electrolyte additives are likewise important under lean conditions, where small changes in interfacial chemistry can strongly affect polysulfide dissolution, shuttle severity, and long-term integrity. Multifunctional additive strategies have been reported to stabilize the electrolyte and regulate polysulfide speciation; for example, small amounts of cationic additives can promote flocculation/solidification of soluble polysulfides, improving cycling stability and redox kinetics even under aggressive conditions<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 59" title="Xu, R. et al. Highly stable lithium sulfur batteries enhanced by flocculation and solidification of soluble polysulfides in routine ether electrolyte. J. Colloid Interface Sci. 649, 223–233 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR59" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1101">59</a></sup>. Broader discussions of electrolyte formulation also emphasize how solvent/salt selection and targeted additives (including SEI-forming compounds such as vinylene carbonate or fluoroethylene carbonate) influence polysulfide behavior and wetting in more practical cell configurations<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 47" title="Ovc-Okene, D., Shankar, L. S., Vizintin, A. &amp; Kun, R. Revitalizing Li–S batteries: the power of electrolyte additives. RSC Adv. 15, 5381–5404 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR47" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1105">47</a></sup>.</p><p>Separator engineering provides an additional lever to improve wetting and mitigate shuttle. Surface modifications, such as coatings with more wettable polymers or conductive layers (e.g., PEDOT:PSS), can increase electrolyte uptake, tune surface energy, and provide sites to immobilize migrating polysulfide species, thereby lowering interfacial resistance and improving utilization under lean electrolyte operation<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 60" title="Kim, A. et al. Recent advances in modified commercial separators for lithium–sulfur batteries. J. Mater. Chem. A 11, 7833–7866 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR60" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1112">60</a></sup>. While detailed process windows (e.g., vacuum level, dwell time, or heating profile) are often proprietary, comparative studies of electrolyte infiltration across cathode architectures consistently show that wetting dynamics depend strongly on pore size, connectivity, and distribution, parameters that must be co-optimized with both assembly strategy and electrolyte formulation<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 61" title="Feng, S. et al. Low-tortuous and dense single-particle-layer electrode for high-energy lithium-sulfur batteries. Energy Environ. Sci. 15, 3842–3853 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR61" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1116">61</a></sup>.</p><p>The cathode architecture should ensure uniform sulfur dispersion, maximize ionic and electronic conductivity, and maintain structural stability during volume expansion and cycling. Promising strategies include hierarchically porous carbon scaffolds and 3D structured current collectors. Emerging sulfur host design focuses on a balanced pore geometry and surface chemistry that holistically addresses polysulfide confinement and ionic transport. Optimal pore geometry should feature a high macroporosity ( &gt; 70% of total pore volume) for ion-buffering and rapid diffusion, a mesoporosity (3-10 nm) for accessible reaction interfaces, and a controlled microporosity to avoid kinetic limitations<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Zhao, C. et al. A high-energy and long-cycling lithium–sulfur pouch cell via a macroporous catalytic cathode with double-end binding sites. Nat. Nanotechnol. 16, 166–173 (2021)." href="#ref-CR62" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1123">62</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Ye, C. et al. Electron-state confinement of polysulfides for highly stable sodium–sulfur batteries. Adv. Mater. 32, 1907557 (2020)." href="#ref-CR63" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1123_1">63</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 64" title="Bi, W. et al. MOF-derived ultrathin carbon nanosheets integrated with telluride nanoparticles: synergistic polysulfide adsorption and catalytic sites for enhanced sulfur redox reactions. Energy Environ. Sci. 18, 1929–1940 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR64" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1126">64</a></sup>. Concurrently, the surface chemistry requires a high density of polar sites (e.g., &gt;5–10% atomic N, predominantly pyridinic) for strong chemisorption. Catalytic systems capable of accelerating polysulfide conversion while adding minimal mass should also contribute to this endeavor. In parallel, the integration of thin SSEs offers another promising avenue. SSEs not only enhance safety and suppress polysulfide shuttling but can also help reduce electrolyte volume, pushing practical SBBs closer to commercial viability in terms of energy density. Although again, this comes with several drawbacks to be overcome.</p><p>Most importantly, future materials and designs must be tested and optimized under practical conditions, that is, with high sulfur loadings and ultra-lean electrolyte levels. Many promising materials perform well under idealized conditions but fail to translate when subjected to realistic constraints. In such demanding configurations, the properties of the sulfur host, catalyst, binder, and current collector, as well as their interactions, may differ significantly from those observed under dilute lab-scale conditions.</p><p>A reliable and commercially relevant assessment of SBBs requires comprehensive evaluation at the full‑cell level. This means calculating energy density in Wh/kg based on the entire cell assembly—accounting for the current collectors, packing density, and the mass of the electrolyte, separator, and casing, rather than on the active sulfur material alone. Only such holistic data enables a direct and meaningful comparison with commercial lithium‑ion batteries, providing an accurate measure of real‑world potential. Consequently, future research must focus not only on electrode materials but also on full‑cell architecture, strategically balancing sulfur loading, electrode thickness, and electrolyte volume to maximize practical energy density and competitiveness.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec7">Low cycling stability</h3><p>Capacity fading remains a critical barrier to the long-term viability of SBBs, particularly in EV applications where a typical performance benchmark is the retention of at least 80% of initial capacity over 1000 cycles, corresponding to a maximum average fade rate of <span class="stix">∼</span>0.02% per cycle. Current high-sulfur-loading and lean-electrolyte LSBs fail to meet this target, exhibiting significant degradation after only 100–200 cycles and capacity fade rates in the range of 0.1% per cycle. This degradation is strongly influenced by cell design, including cathode architecture, electrolyte formulation, and operational parameters such as current rate and depth of discharge.</p><p>The predominant cause of capacity loss in LSBs using conventional ether-based electrolytes is the dissolution of intermediate polysulfides into the electrolyte, leading to irreversible loss of active material. Migrated polysulfides can reach the anode and participate in parasitic side reactions, which not only consume metal ions and polysulfides but also degrade the anode surface, promoting further instability. Additionally, the accumulation of polysulfides in the electrolyte increases its viscosity and decreases ionic mobility, while their deposition, potentially mediating chemical comproportionation and disproportionation chemical reactions, in the separator can further impede mass transport and increase internal resistance. Polysulfides can also chemically react with the lithium nitrate (LiNO₃) electrolyte additive typically used in LSBs and with the organic solvent, degrading it<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 65" title="Shim, J., Ko, T. J. &amp; Yoo, K. Study for an effect of LiNO3 on polysulfide multistep reaction in Li/S battery. J. Ind. Eng. Chem. 80, 283–291 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR65" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1147">65</a></sup>. These failure mechanisms, including DOL polymerization, the triggering of solvent side reactions by S<sub>3</sub><sup>*-</sup> radicals, lithium bis (trifluoromethanesulfonyl) imide (LiTFSI anion decomposition, and LiNO<sub>3</sub> depletion, have been studied in detail using in situ and operando analytical techniques<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 14" title="Yu, J. et al. Mechanistic insights and technical challenges in sulfur-based batteries: a comprehensive in situ/operando monitoring toolbox. ACS Energy Lett. 9, 6178–6214 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR14" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1156">14</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Liu, F.-Q. et al. Upgrading traditional liquid electrolyte via in situ gelation for future lithium metal batteries. Sci. Adv. 4, eaat5383 (2018)." href="#ref-CR66" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1159">66</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Zou, Q. &amp; Lu, Y.-C. Solvent-dictated lithium sulfur redox reactions: an operando UV–vis spectroscopic study.  J. Phys. Chem. Lett. 7, 1518–1525 (2016)." href="#ref-CR67" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1159_1">67</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="France-Lanord, A. et al. Chemical decomposition of the TFSI anion under aqueous basic conditions. PRX Energy 1, 013005 (2022)." href="#ref-CR68" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1159_2">68</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 69" title="Ding, N. et al. Building better lithium-sulfur batteries: from LiNO3 to solid oxide catalyst. Sci. Rep. 6, 33154 (2016)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR69" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1162">69</a></sup>.</p><p>To address these challenges associated with the polysulfide dissolution, several mitigation strategies have been explored, as already outlined in “Low charge/discharge rates and relatively long response times”. Functionalized carbon materials, polar surface coatings, or additives can chemically or physically trap polysulfides within the cathode region. Beyond conventional carbon hosts, metal oxides like TiO₂, MnO₂, and Al₂O₃ offer a distinct advantage by strongly suppressing polysulfide shuttling and improving long-term cycle stability<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Zukalová, M., Vinarčíková, M., Lásková, B. P. &amp; Kavan, L. TiO2 top layer improving the performance of sulfur/carbon composite cathode in Li-sulfur cells. Mater. Chem. Phys. 296, 127246 (2023)." href="#ref-CR70" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1169">70</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Ge, Y. et al. Shape-controlled MnO2 as a sulfur host for high-performance lithium-sulfur batteries. N. J. Chem. 44, 11365–11372 (2020)." href="#ref-CR71" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1169_1">71</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 72" title="Wang, X. et al. Highly electrocatalytic active amorphous Al2O3 in porous carbon assembled on carbon cloth as an independent multifunctional interlayer for advanced lithium-sulfur batteries. Appl. Surf. Sci. 618, 156689 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR72" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1172">72</a></sup>. This benefit, however, is offset by the increased cathode weight they introduce, leading to a trade-off in practical energy density. Separator modifications, such as applying polysulfide-anchoring layers to the cathode-facing side, or encapsulation of sulfur in porous or core-shell structures, have also been proposed<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 43" title="Chen, P.-Y., Cho, C.-S. &amp; Li, C.-C. Enhancing performance of lithium-sulfur batteries through porous carbon network integration in carbonized cotton. Mater. Res. Bull. 170, 112563 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR43" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1176">43</a></sup>. These approaches can be effective in low-to-moderate sulfur loading systems, but often become less efficient under practical high-loading conditions due to saturation of the trapping capacity or mass transport limitations.</p><p>Incorporating electrocatalysts into the cathode is an effective strategy to reduce the residence time of soluble intermediates by accelerating their conversion to insoluble species, thereby reducing polysulfide diffusion and shuttle effects. Although catalysts may introduce new failure modes or add complexity, experimental studies consistently show enhanced cycling stability. The performance benefits, particularly in terms of reduced capacity fade and improved Coulombic efficiency, often outweigh the added cost and fabrication complexity<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Yang, D. et al. Supporting Information Single-Atom Catalysts with Unsaturated Co-N2 Active Sites Based on a C2N 2D-Organic Framework for Efficient Sulfur Redox Reaction. ACS Energy Letters 9, 2083–2091 (2024)." href="#ref-CR73" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1183">73</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Yang, D. et al. Three birds with one arrow: Multifunctional single-atom catalysts enable efficient lithium-sulfur batteries. Energy Storage Mater. 66, 103240 (2024)." href="#ref-CR74" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1183_1">74</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Huang, C. et al. Anionic doping in layered transition metal chalcogenides for robust lithium-sulfur batteries. Angewandte Chemie International Edition, e202420488 (2025)." href="#ref-CR75" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1183_2">75</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 76" title="Huang, C. et al. Electronic Spin Alignment within Homologous NiS2/NiSe2 Heterostructures to Promote Sulfur Redox Kinetics in Lithium-Sulfur Batteries. Adv. Mater. 36, 2400810 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR76" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1186">76</a></sup>.</p><p>However, metallic compound catalysts are themselves susceptible to degradation under extended high-rate cycling. A primary mechanism is metal leaching, where polysulfide interactions cause the dissolution of transition-metal ions (e.g., Co, Fe, Ni, Mn), progressively depleting active sites<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 77" title="Song, Y., Zou, L., Wei, C., Zhou, Y. &amp; Hu, Y. Single-atom electrocatalysts for lithium–sulfur chemistry: Design principle, mechanism, and outlook. Carbon Energy 5, e286 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR77" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1194">77</a></sup>. Catalysts also degrade through phase segregation and agglomeration; for example, unconfined nanosized FeS₂ particles can coalesce or reconstruct into thermodynamically stable yet electrochemically inert phases<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 78" title="Zeng, Z. et al. Nanosized FeS2 particles caged in the hollow carbon shell as a robust polysulfide adsorbent and redox mediator. ACS Sustain. Chem. Eng. 8, 3261–3272 (2020)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR78" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1198">78</a></sup>. Concurrently, surface passivation by insulating Li₂S/Li₂S₂ layers or electrolyte decomposition products blocks electron and ion transport, particularly at high sulfur loadings<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 79" title="Ao, X. et al. Catalyst Passivation and Coping Strategies in Lithium–Sulfur Batteries. ChemSusChem 18, e202500810 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR79" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1202">79</a></sup>. Strategies such as heteroatom doping (e.g., Co-Nₓ, Fe-Nₓ) aim to balance adsorption strength, promoting polysulfide desorption to mitigate this passivation<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 80" title="Cheng, Y. et al. Sulfur-Bridged Dual Fe–N4 Sites to Boost Lithium–Sulfur Battery Performance. J. Am. Chem. Soc. 147, 39805–39817 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR80" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1206">80</a></sup>.</p><p>Replacing conventional liquid electrolytes with non-solvating liquids or SSEs can effectively suppress polysulfide dissolution and shuttle effects<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 26" title="Ji, Y. et al. PIM-1 as a multifunctional framework to enable high-performance solid-state lithium–sulfur batteries. Adv. Funct. Mater. 31, 2104830 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR26" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1213">26</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 27" title="Weller, C., Thieme, S., Härtel, P., Althues, H. &amp; Kaskel, S. Intrinsic shuttle suppression in lithium-sulfur batteries for pouch cell application. J. Electrochem. Soc. 164, A3766 (2017)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR27" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1216">27</a></sup>. However, this often comes at the cost of reduced sulfur utilization due to the dominance of solid-solid reaction pathways, which are kinetically limited. As a result, while such strategies may reduce active material loss, they typically introduce new limitations in stability, rate capability, and energy density, and thus must be carefully optimized<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 81" title="Wan, H. et al. Understanding LiI-LiBr catalyst activity for solid state Li2S/S reactions in an all-solid-state lithium battery. Nano Lett. 21, 8488–8494 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR81" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1220">81</a></sup>.</p><p>Beyond Li-S systems, distinct failure modes emerge based on cation chemistry. In NaSBs, polysulfide solubility and the shuttle effect are reduced, yet sluggish solid-solid conversion and pore blockage become dominant, demanding strategies that enhance solid-state kinetics<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 37" title="Zhang, C. Y. et al. Sodium-sulfur batteries with unprecedented capacity, cycling stability and operation temperature range enabled by a CoFe2O4 catalytic additive under an external magnetic field. Adv. Funct. Mater. 33, 2305908 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR37" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1227">37</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 82" title="Huang, C. et al. Generation of unpaired electrons to promote electron transfer at the cathode of room-temperature sodium sulfur batteries. Chem. Eng. J. 506, 160146 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR82" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1230">82</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 83" title="Zhang, C. Y. et al. Identifying the role of the cationic geometric configuration in spinel catalysts for polysulfide conversion in sodium–sulfur batteries. J. Am. Chem. Soc. 145, 18992–19004 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR83" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1233">83</a></sup>. For Mg-S chemistries, the divalent nature and strong solvation of Mg<sup>2+</sup> ions result in severe kinetic limitations, with slow charge transfer and surface passivation. These issues eclipse the shuttle effect and present a fundamental transport barrier, thus necessitating new electrolyte designs, often centered on complex magnesium salts<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 84" title="Cao, H. et al. Fundamental understanding and material challenges in rechargeable magnesium–sulfur battery: current advances and perspective. Small 21, e07241 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR84" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1239">84</a></sup>. In K-S systems, the poor solubility of potassium polysulfides (e.g., K₂S₂, K₂S₃) forces reaction pathways through high-overpotential solid-phase conversions, leading to inactive sulfide accumulation<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 85" title="Gu, S. et al. Chemical synthesis of K2S2 and K2S3 for probing electrochemical mechanisms in K–S batteries. ACS Energy Lett. 3, 2858–2864 (2018)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR85" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1243">85</a></sup>. Here, research focuses on tailored electrolytes and polar conductive hosts, with solid-state conductors like K₃SbS₄ showing significant promise<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 86" title="Shao, J. et al. K3SbS4 as a potassium superionic conductor with low activation energy for K–S batteries. Angew. Chem. 134, e202200606 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR86" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1247">86</a></sup>.</p><p>The use of redox species to recover lost sulfur, analogous to the recovery of dead lithium in lithium-metal batteries, represents another promising strategy to extend its cycling life. In lithium systems, redox mediators such as the I₃⁻/I⁻ couple have been shown to chemically reactivate electrically isolated lithium and convert inactive species back into electrochemically active forms<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 87" title="Shi, H. et al. Challenges and solutions for lithium–sulfur batteries with lean electrolyte. Adv. Funct. Mater. 33, 2306933 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR87" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1254">87</a></sup>. By extension, introducing suitable redox-active intermediates in SBBs could offer a pathway to chemically rejuvenate electrochemically inactive or “dead” sulfur species, such as isolated M<sub>y</sub>S deposits or sulfur trapped in poorly conductive domains, thus mitigating long-term capacity loss, as proven recently for LSBs<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 88" title="Liu, Z., Chen, M., Zhou, D. &amp; Xiao, Z. Scavenging of “dead sulfur” and “dead lithium” revealed by integrated–heterogeneous catalysis for advanced lithium–sulfur batteries. Adv. Funct. Mater. 33, 2306321 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR88" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1260">88</a></sup>.</p><p>Another major contributor to capacity loss in SBBs is the substantial volume expansion that occurs during the conversion of sulfur to metal sulfides. Upon full lithiation to Li₂S, sulfur undergoes a volume increase of approximately 80-100%. Even greater expansion is observed with some other metals, including 100-120% with sodium (Na₂S), 120-140% with magnesium (MgS), and up to 160-200% with aluminum (Al₂S₃). In contrast, the expansion is more moderate, though still significant, in systems using zinc (70-80% for ZnS) and iron (50-80% for FeS or FeS₂). These large volumetric changes generate considerable mechanical stress within the electrode, leading to cracking, loss of electrical connectivity, and structural degradation of the active material, factors that collectively compromise both battery performance and long-term cycling stability. Loss of connectivity is particularly severe with SSEs, which often require the application of high pressures during cycling, conditions that are impractical for real-world applications.</p><p>To mitigate the volume change limitation, various strategies have been proposed. One effective approach is the use of porous, conductive frameworks that act as mechanical buffers, accommodating the volume fluctuations while maintaining electrical conductivity and structural integrity<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 33" title="Papandrea, B. et al. Three-dimensional graphene framework with ultra-high sulfur content for a robust lithium–sulfur battery. Nano Res. 9, 240–248 (2016)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR33" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1270">33</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 89" title="Liu, F. et al. Metal-organic frameworks derived single atom catalysts for lithium sulfur batteries. Commun. Mater. 6, 185 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR89" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1273">89</a></sup>. These scaffolds can include hierarchically structured carbons, conductive polymers, or composite networks. Additionally, the use of elastic or self-healing polymeric binders has shown promise in maintaining electrode cohesion by absorbing mechanical strain and repairing microcracks formed during cycling<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 90" title="Si, M. et al. A Highly Damping, Crack-Insensitive and Self-Healable Binder for Lithium-Sulfur Battery by Tailoring the Viscoelastic Behavior. Adv. Energy Mater. 14, 2303991 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR90" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1277">90</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 91" title="Lee, J. et al. Stress-tolerant sulfur cathode with a super-stretchable polymer coating via initiated chemical vapor deposition. Commun. Mater. 6, 82 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR91" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1280">91</a></sup>.</p><p>An additional major stability concern in SBBs lies at the anode. To match the high specific capacity of sulfur cathodes, metal anodes, particularly lithium metal, are typically employed. While not unique to sulfur-based systems, lithium metal anodes present significant stability challenges, most notably the formation of dendrites during repeated cycling. These needle-like lithium deposits can lead to poor Coulombic efficiency, rapid capacity degradation, and, critically, internal short circuits that pose serious safety risks, including thermal runaway<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 92" title="Kang, S., Cheng, J., Gao, W. &amp; Cui, L. Toward safer lithium metal batteries: a review. Energy Mater. 3, 300043 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR92" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1288">92</a></sup>.</p><p>To mitigate this, research has focused on strategies that stabilize the lithium interface. One approach involves creating protective interlayers, such as thin Li₃PS₄ or LiF-rich coatings and lithiophilic polymer films, which homogenize current distribution and physically block dendrite nucleation<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 93" title="Sun, G. et al. Design of an ultra-highly stable lithium–sulfur battery by regulating the redox activity of electrocatalyst and the growth of lithium dendrite through localized electric field. ACS nano 19, 871–884 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR93" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1295">93</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 94" title="Narayanan, S. et al. Effect of current density on the solid electrolyte interphase formation at the lithium∣ Li6PS5Cl interface. Nat. Commun. 13, 7237 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR94" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1298">94</a></sup>. In polymer-based solid electrolytes, the incorporation of ceramic nanofillers (e.g., LLZO or LATP) simultaneously enhances mechanical modulus and ionic conductivity, further suppressing dendrite growth<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 95" title="Zhu, Q., Ye, C. &amp; Mao, D. Solid-state electrolytes for lithium–sulfur batteries: challenges, progress, and strategies. Nanomaterials 12, 3612 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR95" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1302">95</a></sup>. Broader strategies also include the design of artificial solid-electrolyte interphases (SEIs), the use of lithium alloys, and structured lithium hosts to promote uniform plating and stripping. A more conservative alternative involves replacing lithium metal with safer anode materials such as graphite or silicon in lithium-ion configurations, or hard carbon in sodium-ion systems. However, these approaches face limitations, particularly with respect to ensuring sufficient availability of active metal ions, as discussed in “Safety concerns”.</p><p>In addition to dendrite-related issues, the continuous formation and degradation of the SEI layer on the metal anode, along with parasitic reactions involving dissolved metal polysulfides and electrolyte decomposition, contribute to the gradual depletion of active metal and electrolyte. In LSBs, this is exacerbated by the consumption of LiNO₃, a widely used electrolyte additive critical for stabilizing the lithium surface and suppressing polysulfide-related side reactions<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 65" title="Shim, J., Ko, T. J. &amp; Yoo, K. Study for an effect of LiNO3 on polysulfide multistep reaction in Li/S battery. J. Ind. Eng. Chem. 80, 283–291 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR65" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1309">65</a></sup>. The loss of LiNO₃ over cycling, coupled with lithium and electrolyte depletion, accelerates capacity fading and may eventually lead to cell failure or operational instability. To address these challenges, current research efforts are focusing on: (i) advanced electrolyte formulations with enhanced metal-ion retention and long-term additive stability; (ii) robust artificial SEIs that limit additive consumption; (iii) cell architectures designed to physically isolate the anode from polysulfide exposure; and (iv) strategies for electrolyte and additive replenishment to enable extended cycle life in high-loading SBBs<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 96" title="Ma, G. et al. A lithium anode protection guided highly-stable lithium–sulfur battery. Chem. Commun. 50, 14209–14212 (2014)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR96" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1313">96</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 97" title="Wu, F. et al. Lithium iodide as a promising electrolyte additive for lithium-sulfur batteries: mechanisms of performance enhancement. Adv. Mater. 27, 101–108 (2014)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR97" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1316">97</a></sup>. Fig.&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig6">6</a> provides an overview of the key mechanisms limiting SBB cycling performance, along with representative approaches that have been proposed to address these challenges.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-6" data-title="Limited cycling stability."><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig6" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 6: Limited cycling stability.</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig6_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-6-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-6-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig6_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 6: Limited cycling stability." loading="lazy" width="685" height="514"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-6-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/6" data-track-dest="link:Figure6 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 6" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-6-desc"><p>Schematic representation of the factors limiting SBB cycling stability and strategies to overcome them.</p></div></div></figure></div><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec8">Limited temperature operation range</h3><p>Due to the complex cathodic conversion reactions and the use of metal anodes, SBBs exhibit strongly temperature-dependent performance, making them particularly vulnerable in extreme thermal environments. These temperature effects significantly influence ion transport, reaction kinetics, and structural stability across the cell components (Fig.&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig7">7</a>)<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 98" title="Yang, H., Zhao, Y., Li, S., Tong, H. &amp; Li, L. Design of Wide-Temperature Lithium-Sulfur Batteries. Batteries Supercaps 7, e202400039 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR98" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1354">98</a></sup>.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-7" data-title="SBB temperature range."><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig7" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 7: SBB temperature range.</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig7_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-7-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-7-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig7_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 7: SBB temperature range." loading="lazy" width="685" height="346"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-7-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/7" data-track-dest="link:Figure7 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 7" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-7-desc"><p>Summary of the main problems and solutions for SBBs working at high and low temperatures.</p></div></div></figure></div><p>At low temperatures, the reaction kinetics is further slowed down, and thus the rate performance and capacity. Besides, the increased viscosity of the electrolyte leads to reduced metal-ion mobility and sluggish polysulfide diffusion, which in turn exacerbates polarization and lowers overall electrochemical performance. Metal deposition at the anode becomes uneven, promoting dendrite growth that may pierce the separator and cause internal short circuits. Simultaneously, localized polysulfide deposition at the cathode is aggravated, compromising the mechanical integrity and conductivity of the electrode.</p><p>At elevated temperatures, the electrolyte becomes thermally unstable and susceptible to oxidative decomposition, which may result in gas generation, pressure buildup, and electrolyte leakage. High temperatures also accelerate polysulfide dissolution and shuttling, leading to severe active material loss and rapid capacity fading. The metal anode undergoes intensified side reactions with the electrolyte, initiating repeated SEI breakdown and repair cycles that continuously consume active metal ions and destabilize the interface. Moreover, the separator experiences mechanical stress from both cathode volume expansion and metal dendrite penetration. Besides, the conventional heat-labile polypropylene (PP) materials also prevent batteries from maintaining long-term cycles beyond 60 °C, further increasing the risk of short circuits and thermal runaway<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 99" title="Xiang, Y. et al. Advanced separators for lithium-ion and lithium–sulfur batteries: a review of recent progress. ChemSusChem 9, 3023–3039 (2016)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR99" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1383">99</a></sup>.</p><p>To address these challenges, several strategies must be employed across the battery system. At the electrolyte level, it is crucial to extend the operational temperature range by selecting solvents with low freezing and high boiling points, and by introducing functional additives that stabilize the SEI layer and suppress flammability. Flame-retardant additives based on phosphorus compounds<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 100" title="Wang, J. et al. Towards a safe lithium–sulfur battery with a flame-inhibiting electrolyte and a sulfur-based composite cathode. Angew. Chem. Int. Ed. 53, 10099–10104 (2014)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR100" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1390">100</a></sup> or halogen-containing materials<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 101" title="Yang, H. et al. An intrinsic flame-retardant organic electrolyte for safe lithium-sulfur batteries. Angew. Chem. Int. Ed. 58, 791–795 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR101" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1394">101</a></sup> are particularly important for mitigating the risk of thermal runaway. In the long term, the development of SSEs may represent a promising direction for enhancing thermal and electrochemical stability.</p><p>At the cathode, the pore structure should be carefully designed and engineered to minimize ion diffusion distances, improving low-temperature kinetics. Incorporating high-activity electrocatalysts can accelerate both M<sub>y</sub>S precipitation and decomposition at low temperatures<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 102" title="Zeng, P. et al. Achieving reversible precipitation-decomposition of reactive Li2S towards high-areal-capacity lithium-sulfur batteries with a wide-temperature range. Energy Storage Mater. 44, 425–432 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR102" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1404">102</a></sup>. At higher temperatures, strongly adsorptive additives help immobilize polysulfides and reduce shuttling. The use of homogeneous catalysts or redox mediators can further modify the M-S reaction pathway, lowering activation energy and enhancing reaction reversibility.</p><p>The anode also requires careful optimization. The adoption of lithium alloy-based anodes (such as Li-Sn or Li-In) can significantly reduce lithium deposition overpotentials, suppress dendrite formation, and broaden the temperature window for stable operation. Besides, improved separator designs can contribute to thermal robustness by incorporating functional coatings that enhance ion transport while offering mechanical barriers against dendrite penetration<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 103" title="Chen, P. et al. Strong chemical interaction between lithium polysulfides and flame-retardant polyphosphazene for lithium–sulfur batteries with enhanced safety and electrochemical performance. Adv. Mater. 33, 2007549 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR103" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1411">103</a></sup>.</p><p>At the system level, integrating active thermal management systems within battery packs can help maintain cell operation within the optimal temperature range. Though effective, this approach adds costs and reduces overall energy density and efficiency. Controlled heating elements can also be used during startup to elevate the battery’s initial temperature, provided that they are coordinated with a responsive and efficient thermal management system<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 104" title="Rao, Z. et al. Thermal safety and thermal management of batteries. Battery Energy 1, 20210019 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR104" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1418">104</a></sup>.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec9">High self-discharge rate and resting capacity fade</h3><p>Conventional SBBs, particularly those employing lithium metal anodes and ether-based electrolytes, suffer from notably high self-discharge rates. Without effective measures to suppress polysulfide migration, capacity losses can exceed 50% within just a few days or even hours at rest, a stark contrast to conventional LIBs, which typically exhibit less than 5% self-discharge over an entire month.</p><p>The primary cause of this elevated self-discharge is the dissolution of intermediate polysulfide species into the electrolyte, initiating the so-called shuttle effect<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 105" title="Mikhaylik, Y. V. &amp; Akridge, J. R. Polysulfide shuttle study in the Li/S battery system. J. Electrochem. Soc. 151, A1969 (2004)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR105" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1433">105</a></sup>. In this parasitic process, dissolved polysulfides migrate to the anode where they undergo reduction, then diffuse back to the cathode and are reoxidized. This redox cycling occurs continuously, even when the battery is idle, leading to steady voltage decay, irreversible loss of active material, and long-term capacity fade.</p><p>Self-discharge and related degradation are particularly pronounced when the battery is stored at intermediate states of charge (SOC), a condition in which a significant fraction of sulfur exists in soluble polysulfide form in a conventional ether-based LSB. This behavior is fundamentally different from that of LIBs, where intermediate SOCs are typically considered optimal for storage. In sulfur-based systems, intermediate SOCs increase the concentration of mobile, redox-active species, intensifying the shuttle effect. However, both high and low SOCs also introduce challenges<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 106" title="Okanishi, K., Hiraoka, K., Watanabe, M. &amp; Seki, S. A Lifetime Evaluation Method for Lithium-Sulfur Batteries. J. Electrochem. Soc. 171, 110532 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR106" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1440">106</a></sup>. At high SOC, elevated cell voltage places greater stress on both electrodes, increases parasitic reaction rates, and increases the driving force for polysulfide migration. At low SOC, the limited metal ion availability can destabilize metal anodes and amplify degradation.</p><p>While intermediate SOC storage can help reduce mechanical and electrochemical stress on the electrodes, effective suppression of polysulfide migration during rest is essential to preserve capacity and extend shelf life. Strategies under investigation include physical barriers (e.g., selective separators), chemical traps (e.g., functionalized interlayers or host materials), and SSEs or alternative electrolytes, which eliminate the solubility of polysulfides altogether. However, some of these approaches come with trade-offs as noted above: methods effective at blocking LiPS diffusion during rest may impair reaction kinetics during operation. To address this, more adaptive solutions can be explored, such as the use of electrolytes that solidify at ambient temperature and melt near operating temperatures, coupled with thermal management systems that selectively activate ion transport only during charge/discharge. While conceptually appealing, this approach may conflict with the need for rapid battery activation, as discussed in “Low charge/discharge rates and relatively long response times”.</p><p>Beyond polysulfide-related effects, side reactions at the anode represent another major contributor to self-discharge and long-term degradation. The electrolyte may slowly decompose over time, particularly under high-voltage or elevated temperature conditions, consuming active lithium and generating irreversible byproducts. In parallel, the SEI on the anode surface may continue to evolve or reform, consuming additional metal ions and electrolyte components. Although these degradation pathways are typically gradual, their cumulative effect results in continuous capacity loss and a decline in open-circuit voltage (OCV), even without cycling.</p><p>To mitigate these degradation mechanisms, several strategies are being actively pursued. Electrolyte engineering focuses on developing formulations with chemically stable solvents and lithium salts less prone to decomposition. Additives such as fluoroethylene carbonate (FEC) or vinylene carbonate (VC) can promote the formation of robust, passivating SEI layers that reduce ongoing side reactions<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 107" title="Song, J.-H. et al. Effect of fluoroethylene carbonate on electrochemical performances of lithium electrodes and lithium-sulfur batteries. J. Electrochem. Soc. 160, A873 (2013)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR107" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1454">107</a></sup>. Surface coatings on the anode, using polymers, ceramics, or hybrid materials, can further stabilize the interface and suppress parasitic reactions<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 108" title="Zhu, B. et al. Poly (dimethylsiloxane) thin film as a stable interfacial layer for high-performance lithium-metal battery anodes. Adv. Mater. 29, 1603755 (2017)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR108" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1458">108</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 109" title="Niu, J. et al. Li metal coated with Li3PO4 film via atomic layer deposition as battery anode. Ionics 27, 2445–2454 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR109" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1461">109</a></sup>. Enhanced thermal management systems also play a key role by maintaining cell temperature within an optimal range, minimizing thermally driven degradation. In parallel, alternative anode designs, including lithium alloys, three-dimensional structured lithium hosts, and safer (albeit lower-capacity) carbon-based anodes, are being explored to improve the stability of the anode-electrolyte interface and reduce self-discharge, among other advantages<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 110" title="Hong, X. et al. Nonlithium metal–sulfur batteries: steps toward a leap. Adv. Mater. 31, 1802822 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR110" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1465">110</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 111" title="Kong, L. L. et al. Lithium–magnesium alloy as a stable anode for lithium–sulfur battery. Adv. Funct. Mater. 29, 1808756 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR111" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1468">111</a></sup>. Fig.&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig8">8</a> summarizes the main mechanisms responsible for SBB self-discharge and highlights some of the strategies that are being explored to mitigate these effects.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-8" data-title="SBB self-discharge."><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig8" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 8: SBB self-discharge.</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig8_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-8-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-8-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig8_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 8: SBB self-discharge." loading="lazy" width="685" height="623"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-8-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/8" data-track-dest="link:Figure8 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 8" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-8-desc"><p>Schematic representation of the factors driving SBB self-discharge and strategies to overcome them.</p></div></div></figure></div><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec10">Poor thermal dissipation</h3><p>Heat transport, both internal and external, is generally less efficient in SBBs than in conventional LIBs, primarily due to the intrinsically low thermal conductivity of both elemental sulfur and the discharge product metal sulfide (Fig.&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig9">9</a> and Table&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Tab2">2</a>). Furthermore, the sulfur-carbon composite cathodes commonly used in these systems are typically low in density and highly porous, further reducing their ability to conduct heat across the electrode stack. This poor thermal conductivity impedes uniform heat distribution and exacerbates temperature gradients within the cell.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-9" data-title="Heat dissipation."><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig9" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 9: Heat dissipation.</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig9_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-9-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-9-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig9_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 9: Heat dissipation." loading="lazy" width="685" height="472"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-9-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/9" data-track-dest="link:Figure9 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 9" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-9-desc"><p>Scheme of the factors limiting internal and external heat dissipation in SBBs and solutions to overcome this limitation.</p></div></div></figure></div><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-2"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab2" data-test="table-caption">Table 2 Comparison of heat dissipation performance metrics between current laboratory-scale LSBs and commercial LIBs</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/tables/2" aria-label="Full size table 2"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p>In addition, the complex and sluggish multi-step redox reactions at the sulfur cathode are associated with significant energy losses and often proceed in an inhomogeneous manner, generating localized and non-uniform heat, particularly under high-rate and high-loading conditions. As a result, sulfur cathodes can generate notable heat and are especially prone to the formation of hotspots at elevated C-rates and under suboptimal conditions such as poor electrolyte wetting. These thermal inhomogeneities can also lead to uneven ion release, which may further promote non-uniform metal deposition at the anode, increasing the risk of dendrite formation and raising concerns about thermal runaway<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 112" title="Gao, R. et al. Unraveling the coupling effect between cathode and anode toward practical lithium–sulfur batteries. Adv. Mater. 36, 2303610 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR112" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1686">112</a></sup>.</p><p>Additionally, while commercial LIBs benefit from mature and well-integrated thermal management systems, SBBs, still at a relatively low technology readiness level (TRL), lack efficient, scalable, and lightweight thermal management solutions that are specifically tailored to the unique thermal and electrochemical characteristics of sulfur chemistries, especially in high-power or large-format applications.</p><p>Addressing the thermal dissipation challenges in SBBs requires a multi-faceted approach involving both materials engineering and system-level design. At the materials level, improving the thermal conductivity of the cathode can be achieved by incorporating small amounts of thermally conductive additives such as graphene, carbon nanotubes, or metal nanowires into the sulfur-carbon composite<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 113" title="Fang, R. et al. The regulating role of carbon nanotubes and graphene in lithium-ion and lithium–sulfur batteries. Adv. Mater. 31, 1800863 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR113" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1696">113</a></sup>. These additives can form percolative networks that facilitate heat transport without significantly compromising energy density, although costs need to be carefully considered for the solution to become viable. Most importantly, optimizing cathode architecture to reduce porosity and improve structural uniformity can help minimize localized heating and enhance thermal diffusion. At the cell level, improving electrolyte wetting and distribution is essential to avoid dry zones that may lead to hotspots during high-rate operation. Advanced separator designs with enhanced wettability and thermal stability can also contribute to more uniform heat management across the cell.</p><p>On the system side, the integration of lightweight thermal interface materials (TIMs) and passive cooling elements, such as heat spreaders or phase change materials (PCMs), can help stabilize temperature profiles during operation<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 114" title="Goli, P. &amp; Balandin, A. A. in Fourteenth Intersociety Conference on Thermal and Thermomechanical Phenomena in Electronic Systems (ITherm). 1390–1393 (IEEE)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR114" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1704">114</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 115" title="Pei, H. et al. Efficient thermal management of lithium-sulfur batteries by highly thermally conductive LBL-assembled composite separators. Electrochim. Acta 407, 139807 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR115" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1707">115</a></sup>. Active cooling solutions, already common in LIB packs, may be adapted for sulfur-based systems, provided they are tailored to the unique thermal and mechanical properties of the materials involved. Furthermore, real-time thermal monitoring and control via smart BMSs, potentially enhanced by AI algorithms, can dynamically adjust operating parameters to avoid thermal runaway and extend battery life. Developing such adaptive thermal control strategies is essential for the safe and reliable implementation of high-energy SBBs in practical applications.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec11">Safety concerns</h3><p>Current SBB designs face significant safety challenges that continue to hinder their commercial deployment (Fig.&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig10">10</a>). The primary concerns stem from the conventional use of reactive alkali metal anodes, particularly lithium and sodium, to match the high capacities of sulfur cathodes. While these anodes offer exceptionally high theoretical capacities, they are inherently prone to dendrite formation during repeated charge/discharge cycles, a challenge not unique to SBBs but common to all lithium- and sodium-metal battery systems<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 116" title="Wang, J. et al. Suppressing the shuttle effect and dendrite growth in lithium–sulfur batteries. Acs Nano 14, 9819–9831 (2020)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR116" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1722">116</a></sup>. Over time, dendrites can grow across the separator and reach the cathode, causing internal short circuits. In severe cases, this can lead to thermal runaway, resulting in cell rupture, fire, or even explosion.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-10" data-title="Safety concerns."><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig10" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 10: Safety concerns.</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig10_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-10-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-10-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig10_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 10: Safety concerns." loading="lazy" width="685" height="377"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-10-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/10" data-track-dest="link:Figure10 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 10" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-10-desc"><p>Schematic illustration of the key safety concerns in SBBs. Key safety concerns: the use of volatile and toxic electrolyte solvents and reactive metal anodes, along with potential strategies to mitigate these risks.</p></div></div></figure></div><p>Safety risks in conventional SBBs are further exacerbated by the properties of other cell components. The ether-based organic electrolytes, particularly 1,3-dioxolane (DOL) and 1,2-dimethoxyethane (DME), commonly used in LSBs due to their superior compatibility with LiPSs, are highly volatile and combustible. Moreover, the carbon-sulfur composite cathode, though critical for ensuring electrical conductivity and accommodating high sulfur loading, is typically composed of flammable carbonaceous materials. In the event of an internal short circuit or thermal runaway, these components substantially elevate the risk of fire or catastrophic cell failure.</p><p>Experimental studies of large-format Li–S pouch cells have shown that thermal runaway behavior often initiates at the cathode side and dramatically accelerates when molten sulfur and lithium metal interact, creating intense exothermic reactions characteristic of Li–S chemistry<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 117" title="Huang, L. et al. Thermal runaway routes of large-format lithium-sulfur pouch cell batteries. Joule 6, 906–922 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR117" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1751">117</a></sup>. Importantly, this behavior can occur even in cells with thermally stable electrolytes because the unavoidable short-circuiting induced by molten electrode materials dominates the runaway pathway. Moreover, ether-based electrolytes with relatively low boiling temperatures contribute to rapid pressure buildup and physical failure during heating, further increasing fire risk compared to LIB electrolytes.</p><p>The polysulfide shuttle contributes to hot spot formation and uneven current distribution, effectively lowering the threshold for thermal runaway compared to LIBs. At the battery pack level, these characteristics imply that SBB cells may enter thermal runaway at lower temperatures and with different propagation dynamics, necessitating more advanced thermal management and isolation strategies to prevent cascading failures across multiple cells. Additionally, the potential release of toxic sulfur-containing gases (e.g., H₂S) during thermal decomposition introduces safety considerations unique to SBB systems.</p><p>Besides, the volatile ether-based solvents pose additional safety risks, especially in large-scale manufacturing environments. DME is classified as harmful if inhaled or ingested, while DOL is known to form explosive peroxides upon prolonged exposure to air<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 118" title="Ma, X. et al. Sustainable electrolytes: design principles and recent advances. Chem.–A Eur. J. 30, e202400332 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR118" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1762">118</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 119" title="Yang, X. et al. Control the explosive polymerization of 1, 3-dioxolane in LiPF6 electrolyte by Lewis acid-base interactions. J. Energy Storage 101, 113793 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR119" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1765">119</a></sup>. Moreover, ether-based electrolytes are chemically unstable at high voltages, leading to gas generation and the formation of reactive decomposition products, which further compromise battery safety, particularly in the presence of lithium metal. Furthermore, cathodes are generally processed using toxic organic solvents, most notably N-methyl-2-pyrrolidone (NMP), which is classified as reprotoxic in the European Union.</p><p>To address these concerns, several strategies are being actively pursued. One promising solution is the adoption of SSEs, which can physically block dendrite propagation and eliminate the risk of flammable solvent leakage<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 120" title="Meabe, L. et al. Solid-state electrolytes for safe rechargeable lithium metal batteries: a strategic view. Mater. Futures 2, 033501 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR120" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1772">120</a></sup>. These materials, such as sulfide-based<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 121" title="Zhu, X., Wang, L., Bai, Z., Lu, J. &amp; Wu, T. Sulfide-based all-solid-state lithium–sulfur batteries: challenges and perspectives. Nano-micro Lett. 15, 75 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR121" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1776">121</a></sup> or oxide-based SSEs<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 122" title="Lu, Y. et al. Highly stable garnet solid electrolyte based Li-S battery with modified anodic and cathodic interfaces. Energy Storage Mater. 15, 282–290 (2018)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR122" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1780">122</a></sup>, offer improved safety by providing higher mechanical strength and thermal stability. However, despite these advantages, solid-state systems face significant challenges. Achieving intimate and stable interfacial contact between the electrolyte and electrode materials is particularly difficult. To achieve this, significant external pressure is often applied during cell assembly to ensure intimate contact at the interfaces. A high external pressure is often required to be maintained during cycling to keep good interfacial contact in ceramic SSEs, which is impractical for commercial-scale applications. Besides, as previously discussed, confining the metal-sulfur conversion reaction entirely to the solid phase introduces additional limitations in reaction kinetics and overall sulfur utilization, further complicating the implementation of solid-state designs. Compounding these issues is the pronounced chemical instability at the anode-electrolyte interface. SSEs, typically composed of sulfide-, oxide-, or halide-based inorganic compounds, while offering good ionic conductivity, are not thermodynamically inert. When directly interfaced with metal anodes, spontaneous chemical reactions may occur, resulting in the formation of undesirable interfacial byproducts such as LiCO<sub>3</sub> or other electrochemically inactive compounds<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 123" title="Banerjee, A., Wang, X., Fang, C., Wu, E. A. &amp; Meng, Y. S. Interfaces and interphases in all-solid-state batteries with inorganic solid electrolytes. Chem. Rev. 120, 6878–6933 (2020)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR123" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1786">123</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 124" title="Xu, L. et al. Interfaces in solid-state lithium batteries. Joule 2, 1991–2015 (2018)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR124" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1789">124</a></sup>. These byproducts are often electronically insulating and poorly ionically conductive, giving rise to so-called “space charge layers” or passivation layers at the interface. Such layers impede efficient lithium-ion transport and significantly increase interfacial resistance. Worse still, these side reactions are frequently irreversible, meaning that with continued cycling, the electrochemical activity at the interface progressively deteriorates, polarization increases, and overall battery performance declines rapidly. While surface coatings and interface engineering strategies have been proposed to mitigate these reactions, their effectiveness is constrained by challenges related to material compatibility, processing complexity, and long-term stability. On top of this, it has been shown that in SSE systems, metals can still penetrate along electrolyte grain boundaries and grow into dendrites<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 125" title="Sun, M. et al. Visualizing lithium dendrite formation within solid-state electrolytes. ACS Energy Lett. 6, 451–458 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR125" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1794">125</a></sup>.</p><p>Another approach involves replacing lithium metal with alternative anode materials. Candidates such as silicon<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 126" title="Piwko, M. et al. Hierarchical columnar silicon anode structures for high energy density lithium sulfur batteries. J. Power Sources 351, 183–191 (2017)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR126" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1801">126</a></sup>, tin metal alloys<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 127" title="Cheng, X. B., Peng, H. J., Huang, J. Q., Wei, F. &amp; Zhang, Q. Dendrite-Free Nanostructured Anode: Entrapment of Lithium in a 3D Fibrous Matrix for Ultra-Stable Lithium–Sulfur Batteries. Small 10, 4257–4263 (2014)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR127" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1805">127</a></sup>, and even conventional graphite<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 128" title="Jeschull, F., Brandell, D., Edström, K. &amp; Lacey, M. J. A stable graphite negative electrode for the lithium–sulfur battery. Chem. Commun. 51, 17100–17103 (2015)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR128" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1809">128</a></sup> and hard carbon<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 129" title="Kohl, M., Borrmann, F., Althues, H. &amp; Kaskel, S. Hard carbon anodes and novel electrolytes for long-cycle-life room temperature sodium-sulfur full cell batteries. Adv. Energy Mater. 6, 1502185 (2016)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR129" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1813">129</a></sup> are being actively explored, either in their pure form or as part of hybrid/composite architectures. Although these materials generally offer lower energy densities compared to pure lithium, they can significantly improve safety by suppressing dendrite formation and enhancing cycling stability.</p><p>The use of Si, Sn, and various metal alloys as anode materials introduces a new set of challenges, chief among them being interfacial instability<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Je, M., Han, D.-Y., Ryu, J. &amp; Park, S. Constructing pure Si anodes for advanced lithium batteries. Acc. Chem. Res. 56, 2213–2224 (2023)." href="#ref-CR130" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1820">130</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Li, J. et al. Crystallographic engineering in micron-sized SiO x anode material toward stable high-energy-density lithium-ion batteries. ACS nano 19, 16096–16109 (2025)." href="#ref-CR131" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1820_1">131</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 132" title="Kim, C. et al. Development and evaluation of Sn foil anode for sodium-ion batteries. Small 17, 2102618 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR132" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1823">132</a></sup>. This instability encompasses both mechanical degradation and chemical incompatibility. These anodes store lithium through alloying reactions, such as the well-known Li + Si → Li<sub>3.75</sub>Si, which, although beneficial in terms of theoretical capacity, induce massive volumetric changes during cycling, often expanding to three to four times their original size. Such extreme volume fluctuations cause repeated and severe mechanical mismatches at the interface, leading to delamination, cracking, and ultimately the loss of electronic contact. As a result, the alloying anode may degrade rapidly over cycles, leading to sharp capacity fade and shortened battery lifespan.</p><p>Another major manufacturing challenge associated with non-metal anodes is the need to introduce charge-carrying cations into the system. In conventional lithium-ion and sodium-ion batteries with graphite or hard carbon anodes, lithium and sodium are typically incorporated within the discharged cathode material. However, in sulfur-based cathodes, this necessitates the use of compounds such as Li<sub>2</sub>S or Na<sub>2</sub>S during cell assembly. These sulfides are highly air-sensitive, complicating both electrode fabrication and battery assembly<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Mollania, H. et al. Nanostructured Li2S Cathodes for Silicon–Sulfur Batteries. ACS Appl. Mater. Interfaces 15, 58462–58475 (2023)." href="#ref-CR133" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1836">133</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Qi, X. et al. Air-stable Li2S Cathodes enabled by an in situ-formed Li+ conductor for graphite-Li2S pouch cells. Adv. Mater. 36, 2310756 (2024)." href="#ref-CR134" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1836_1">134</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 135" title="Tang, W. et al. Stable cycling of sodium all-solid-state batteries with high-capacity cathode presodiation. Adv. Energy Mater.15, 2405678 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR135" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1839">135</a></sup>. Moreover, Li<sub>2</sub>S or Na<sub>2</sub>S are electronically insulating and require significant overpotentials for activation during the initial cycle. Additionally, efficient utilization of the active material depends on achieving a highly dispersed distribution of sulfide particles, ideally at the nanometer scale, within the cathode to facilitate ion and electron transport throughout both the initial and subsequent cycles<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 133" title="Mollania, H. et al. Nanostructured Li2S Cathodes for Silicon–Sulfur Batteries. ACS Appl. Mater. Interfaces 15, 58462–58475 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR133" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1848">133</a></sup>. However, achieving such a fine and uniform dispersion remains a significant challenge.</p><p>On the other hand, assembling SBBs with a sulfur cathode and a non-metal anode simplifies electrode processing, allowing for the use of aqueous-based fabrication methods and water-soluble binders. However, this configuration introduces a critical challenge: how to introduce and balance metal ions within the system, since neither electrode initially contains the active metal or ion carrier. Unlike conventional LSBs and Na-S batteries that employ lithium or sodium metal anodes, these systems require a deliberate strategy to introduce and balance alkali metal ions within the cell. Several approaches have been developed or proposed to address this issue.</p><p>A widely adopted approach is the prelithiation or presodiation of the anode, which can be achieved through either chemical or electrochemical methods<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 136" title="Frankenstein, L. et al. Elucidating ‘Transfer-Lithiation’from graphite to Si within composite anodes during pre-lithiation and regular charging. ChemSusChem 18, e202401290 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR136" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1859">136</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 137" title="Moeez, I., Jung, H.-G., Lim, H.-D. &amp; Chung, K. Y. Presodiation strategies and their effect on electrode–electrolyte interphases for high-performance electrodes for sodium-ion batteries. ACS Appl. Mater. Interfaces 11, 41394–41401 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR137" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1862">137</a></sup>. In the chemical approach, stabilized lithium or sodium compounds, such as Li₂O, Na₂O, or stabilized lithium/sodium metal powders (SLMP/SNMP), are introduced to react with the anode material and release Li⁺ or Na⁺ ions. Another strategy involves depositing a controlled thin layer of lithium or sodium metal onto the anode surface using vacuum-based techniques such as pulsed laser deposition. Alternatively, electrochemical prelithiation/ presodiation consists of pre-cycling the anode in a half-cell configuration against lithium or sodium metal, followed by disassembly and reassembly into a full cell<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 138" title="Jin, L. et al. Progress and perspectives on pre-lithiation technologies for lithium ion capacitors. Energy Environ. Sci. 13, 2341–2362 (2020)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR138" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1866">138</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 139" title="Matsuzaki, M. et al. Application of Na2CO3 as a sacrificial electrode additive in Na-ion batteries to compensate for the sodium deficiency in Na2/3 [Fe1/2Mn1/2] O2. Batteries Supercaps 7, e202400009 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR139" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1869">139</a></sup>. While these methods offer precise control over the metal-ion inventory, they add complexity and cost to the manufacturing process, and raise safety and scalability concerns, thereby limiting their application primarily to the laboratory scale.</p><p>Another strategy is the incorporation of sacrificial lithium or sodium additives into the sulfur cathode. These additives, such as LiN₃, NaN₃, LiBH₄, or NaBH₄, decompose during initial cycling (or via thermal activation) to release the necessary alkali metal ions<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Wang, P.-F., Wang, J.-C., Zhang, N., Tian, S.-H. &amp; Yi, T.-F. High-energy SiO-sulfur battery with preloaded Li3N in a cathode as a lithiation reagent. Langmuir 40, 8678–8684 (2024)." href="#ref-CR140" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1876">140</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Li, Q. et al. Interphasial Pre-lithiation and reinforcement of micro-si anode through fluorine-free electrolytes. Angew. Chem. 135, e202310297 (2023)." href="#ref-CR141" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1876_1">141</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Nieto, N. et al. Sodium Mesoxalate as sacrificial salt for biomass-derived hard carbon/polyanionic cathode Na-ion full cells. Batteries Supercaps 8, 2500252 (2025)." href="#ref-CR142" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1876_2">142</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 143" title="Chen, Y. et al. Na2S Presodiation enables long cycling anode-free sodium batteries via rapid spontaneous reactions. Adv. Funct. Mater. 35, 2502343 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR143" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1879">143</a></sup>. However, this method requires careful control of additive content and handling, as decomposition reactions may involve gas evolution or introduce side reactions.</p><p>A complementary approach involves designing the electrolyte as a reservoir of excess lithium or sodium. This could be achieved using highly concentrated salt formulations that store additional ions or by incorporating mobile metal-ion salts that release Li⁺ or Na⁺ during early cycles<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 144" title="Chen, S. et al. Active organic salts enabling non-intrusive electrolyte presodiation strategy. Adv. Mater. 37, 2502251 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR144" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1886">144</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 145" title="Haneke, L. et al. Insights into electrolytic pre-lithiation: a thorough analysis using silicon thin film anodes. Small 19, 2206092 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR145" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1889">145</a></sup>. However, this strategy alone typically lacks the capacity to fully compensate for the missing metal inventory and is more effective when combined with other methods.</p><p>On the other hand, to overcome the safety concerns of organic solvents, aqueous SBBs have also been proposed<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 146" title="Liu, J. et al. Sulfur-based aqueous batteries: electrochemistry and strategies. J. Am. Chem. Soc. 143, 15475–15489 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR146" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1896">146</a></sup>. Aqueous SBBs aim to combine the high theoretical energy density of sulfur redox chemistry with the inherent safety, low cost, and environmental friendliness of water-based electrolytes. The use of aqueous electrolytes eliminates the risk of flammable organic solvents and significantly enhances thermal and chemical stability, making them attractive for grid-scale and stationary applications.</p><p>In typical aqueous sulfur battery designs, elemental sulfur or polysulfide species are used as the cathodic active material, while the anode must be carefully selected to maintain chemical stability in aqueous environments. Materials such as Zn, Sn, and Al have been widely investigated as aqueous-compatible anodes due to their favorable electrochemical stability in neutral or mildly acidic aqueous electrolytes<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Zeng, G. et al. Modulating the solvation structure to enhance amorphous solid electrolyte interface formation for ultra-stable aqueous zinc anode. Energy Environ. Sci. 18, 1683–1695 (2025)." href="#ref-CR147" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1903">147</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Zhou, W., Ding, S., Zhao, D. &amp; Chao, D. An energetic Sn metal aqueous battery. Joule 7, 1104–1107 (2023)." href="#ref-CR148" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1903_1">148</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 149" title="Jia, B. E. et al. Rechargeable aqueous aluminum-ion battery: progress and outlook. Small 18, 2107773 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR149" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1906">149</a></sup>. These elements are also abundant, low-cost, and capable of undergoing reversible redox reactions, making them particularly suitable for coupling with sulfur-based cathodes. Additionally, sulfur has also been proposed as an anode material coupled with an iodine cathode and a Na⁺ charge carrier<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 150" title="Chen, Q. et al. High-reversibility sulfur anode for advanced aqueous battery. Adv. Mater. 36, 2309038 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR150" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1910">150</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 151" title="Wei, C. et al. A universal strategy toward low-cost aqueous sulfur–iodine batteries. Adv. Funct. Mater. 33, 2212644 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR151" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1913">151</a></sup>, offering a novel electrochemical configuration for aqueous sulfur batteries.</p><p>As for Li, Na, and K systems, although Li, Na, and K metals react violently with water and are thus not stable in aqueous environments, their ionic forms (Li + , Na + , K + ) have been successfully utilized as charge carriers in certain aqueous battery configurations. These typically rely on the use of insertion-type anode materials capable of reversibly intercalating these alkali ions<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 152" title="Wang, B. et al. An energetic K+-S aqueous battery with 96% sulfur redox utilization. Joule 8, 2033–2048 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR152" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1920">152</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 153" title="Wang, H., Bi, S., Zhang, Y., Tian, J. &amp; Niu, Z. A high-energy aqueous all-sulfur battery. Angew. Chem. Int. Ed. 63, e202317825 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR153" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1923">153</a></sup>. However, structural stability of these electrodes remains a critical bottleneck, and related research is still at an early exploratory stage.</p><p>Aqueous SBBs offer significant advantages in terms of safety and environmental compatibility, making them strong candidates for next-generation low-cost, long-life, and large-scale energy storage systems. Nonetheless, their practical development faces several technological hurdles. Most notably, the theoretical electrochemical stability window of water is limited to 1.23 V, which significantly constrains the operating voltage range of aqueous battery systems and, by extension, their achievable energy density. To overcome this limitation, “water-in-salt” super-concentrated electrolytes have been developed to partially extend this window to above 2.5 V, i.e., in the range of SBBs based on organic electrolytes<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 154" title="Kumar, M. &amp; Nagaiah, T. C. High energy density aqueous rechargeable sodium-ion/sulfur batteries in ‘water in salt” electrolyte. Energy Storage Mater. 49, 390–400 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR154" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1931">154</a></sup>.</p><p>In addition, sulfur’s low solubility in water and the sluggish kinetics of aqueous sulfur redox reactions can limit performance. Furthermore, polysulfides may exhibit diverse speciation behaviors within aqueous electrolytes, potentially leading to complex reaction pathways, side reactions, and interfacial instability. Current research efforts are addressing these issues through multiple approaches. The incorporation of electrocatalysts has proven to be an effective strategy for accelerating redox kinetics and reducing overpotentials, especially through the design of cathode interfaces that promote synergistic electronic and ionic transport<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 155" title="Feng, Y. et al. High-valent Thiosulfate Redox electrochemistry for advanced sulfur-based aqueous batteries. J. Am. Chem. Soc. 146, 25343–25349 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR155" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1938">155</a></sup>. Tuning the pH environment is also a critical method, as the decomposition potentials of water shift under different acidic or alkaline conditions, potentially expanding the usable electrochemical window of the cell<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 156" title="Yang, C. et al. Unique aqueous Li-ion/sulfur chemistry with high energy density and reversibility. Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. 114, 6197–6202 (2017)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR156" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1942">156</a></sup>. Besides, hybrid electrolytes and redox mediators are also being developed to enable more efficient aqueous SBB systems<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 28" title="Liu, Y. et al. Electrolyte solutions design for lithium-sulfur batteries. Joule 5, 2323–2364 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR28" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1946">28</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 157" title="Wu, W., Wang, S., Lin, L., Shi, H.-Y. &amp; Sun, X. A dual-mediator for a sulfur cathode approaching theoretical capacity with low overpotential in aqueous Zn–S batteries. Energy Environ. Sci. 16, 4326–4333 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR157" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1949">157</a></sup>.</p><p>Additionally, ongoing research aims to develop non-flammable or flame-retardant cathode additives, separators, and liquid electrolytes<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 158" title="Lin, F. et al. Nonflammable electrolyte for rechargeable lithium battery with sulfur based composite cathode materials. J. Power Sources 223, 18–22 (2013)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR158" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1956">158</a></sup>, incorporate thermal shutdown mechanisms, and apply protective coatings to both anode and cathode materials to further minimize the risk of thermal runaway and fire<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 159" title="Cui, C. et al. An armor-like artificial solid electrolyte interphase layer for high performance lithium-sulfur batteries. Appl. Mater. Today 24, 101108 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR159" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1960">159</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 160" title="Castillo, J. et al. Graphene-based sulfur cathodes and dual salt-based sparingly solvating electrolytes: a perfect marriage for high performing, safe, and long cycle life lithium-sulfur prototype batteries. Adv. Energy Mater. 14, 2302378 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR160" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1963">160</a></sup>. These solutions, while promising, must be integrated without compromising the high energy density and cost-effectiveness that make LSBs attractive in the first place. Ultimately, improving the safety of LSBs will require a multifaceted approach, combining materials innovation, cell design optimization, and advanced thermal and mechanical management systems to ensure stability during both operation and storage.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec12">Relatively high manufacturing costs and infrastructure compatibility</h3><p>While SBBs are often promoted as a lower-cost alternative to conventional LIBs, largely due to the abundance and low cost of sulfur, the actual cost estimates of current LSB technologies remain relatively high. One of the primary reasons is the use of lithium metal anodes, which necessitate stringent manufacturing conditions, including moisture- and oxygen-free environments, to prevent degradation and safety hazards. These requirements add considerable complexity and expense to the cell fabrication process.</p><p>In addition, LSBs typically employ ether-based electrolytes, which, while effective at dissolving LiPS and thus accelerating and extending the Li-S reaction, are more expensive and pose several drawbacks. These solvents are toxic, highly flammable, and unstable at elevated voltages, limiting the operating window of the battery and increasing safety concerns. Their volatility also demands careful handling and controlled processing conditions, which further escalate production costs.</p><p>Another cost-related factor is the lithium salt conventionally used in LSB electrolytes. LiTFSI is commonly used due to its high chemical and thermal stability, as well as its compatibility with polysulfide chemistry. However, LiTFSI is significantly more expensive, often more than twice the cost of LiPF₆, the standard salt used in commercial LIBs, placing additional pressure on the overall cost structure of LSBs.</p><p>Addressing these cost issues will require a shift toward alternative electrolyte systems, ideally based on non-flammable, non-toxic solvents that are stable across wider voltage windows and compatible with lower-cost lithium salts. Moreover, replacing lithium metal anodes with alternative materials such as silicon or even graphite, and potentially lithium ions with alternative elements such as sodium, could alleviate some of the safety and cost concerns. However, such approaches introduce new challenges, as noted above.</p><p>Furthermore, as a low TRL technology, SBBs currently lack a mature manufacturing ecosystem. This, combined with their dependence on some costly materials and sensitive, often low-throughput processing techniques, significantly elevates production costs. To enable commercial viability, the manufacturing infrastructure for SBBs must be optimized for scalable, high-throughput, and cost-effective production. In parallel, the supply chain for specialized components, including catalytic additives, advanced binders, and functionalized separators, must be established and industrialized. However, some of these components may prove difficult or costly to scale, presenting additional barriers to widespread adoption.</p><p>More specifically, the dry processing techniques emerging in LIB manufacturing, offering cost, environmental, health, safety, and sustainability benefits (discussed in “Prospects for SBB manufacturing”), fundamentally alter the microstructure and transport properties of sulfur cathodes compared to conventional slurry-cast electrodes. Dry processing typically yields denser, less porous electrodes. While beneficial for volumetric energy density, this reduced porosity can impede electrolyte infiltration and ionic transport, posing a challenge for thick, high-loading cathodes. To address transport limitations, highly porous, binder-free electrodes offer a promising alternative. These structures form open, interconnected networks that enhance electrolyte access and ionic percolation. However, their lack of polymeric binders can compromise mechanical integrity and electronic contact. Therefore, a key design challenge lies in balancing high porosity for transport with sufficient robustness for stability, whether through advanced binder systems or tailored dry-processing parameters.</p><p>Besides, there exist charging/power supply compatibility issues between the requirements of SBBs and those of current standard LIBs. The discharge voltage plateau of LSBs (1.8–2.4 V) is significantly lower than that of LIBs (3.0–4.2 V), resulting in potential incompatibility with existing electronic device power management modules. This mismatch may lead to device startup failure or reduced operational efficiency. Furthermore, the discharge voltage curve exhibits multi-plateau characteristics, imposing stricter requirements on the stability of power management systems due to its dynamic variations.</p><p>During charging, SBBs may require specific voltage/current charging protocols that are incompatible with conventional LIB charging strategies. Additionally, their high capacity necessitates more complex charging management phases (e.g., pre-charging, constant current, and constant voltage phases). Therefore, it is essential for developers to accurately assess the state of charge in SBBs and to design optimized charging algorithms tailored to their unique electrochemical behavior<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 161" title="Propp, K. et al. Improved state of charge estimation for lithium-sulfur batteries. J. Energy Storage 26, 100943 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR161" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e1997">161</a></sup>. In addition, users must rely on dedicated chargers compatible with these specific protocols, which can impact overall convenience and user experience.</p><p>To address voltage fluctuations during discharge, it is critical to develop adaptive voltage regulation algorithms that dynamically adjust output power based on real-time battery states. Alternatively, power management chips with wide input voltage ranges can be adopted to adapt to the discharge voltage characteristics of LSBs<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 162" title="Fotouhi, A., Auger, D. J., Propp, K. &amp; Longo, S. Lithium–sulfur battery state-of-charge observability analysis and estimation. IEEE Trans. Power Electron. 33, 5847–5859 (2017)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR162" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2004">162</a></sup>. For charging strategy compatibility, the industry must establish standardized charging protocols for SBBs, clearly defining parameter ranges for voltage, current, and temperature<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 163" title="Turksoy, A., Teke, A. &amp; Alkaya, A. A comprehensive overview of the DC-DC converter-based battery charge balancing methods in electric vehicles. Renew. Sustain. Energy Rev. 133, 110274 (2020)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR163" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2008">163</a></sup>. However, challenges remain in harmonizing these protocols with legacy infrastructure and ensuring interoperability across heterogeneous charging systems.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec13">Environmental impact and recycling challenges</h3><p>Like other battery technologies, SBBs face significant environmental challenges related to recycling, disposal, and materials sustainability. While established recycling practices already exist for metal current collectors (Cu and Al foils) and metal anodes (e.g., Li), two additional aspects require particular attention in the context of SBBs: the electrolyte and binder materials commonly used in current LSB liquid-cell designs.</p><p>Ether-based solvents, particularly DOL and DME, pose substantial safety risks, as discussed above, and environmental issues, especially when evaluated through the lens of green chemistry and long-term sustainability. Both DOL and DME are volatile organic compounds (VOCs) with low boiling points (<span class="stix">∼</span>75 °C), making them prone to evaporation and thus significant contributors to air pollution. Additionally, these ether solvents are not readily biodegradable, raising concerns about environmental persistence and contamination of soil and water during battery production or disposal. Their use requires strict solvent recovery and ventilation systems, and improper handling can lead to ground-level ozone formation, which is regulated in many jurisdictions.</p><p>To reduce the environmental impact of SBB electrolytes, researchers are exploring various alternatives. Fluorinated ethers, while showing excellent performance and being more electrochemically stable<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 164" title="Drvarič Talian, S. et al. Fluorinated ether based electrolyte for high-energy lithium–sulfur batteries: Li+ solvation role behind reduced polysulfide solubility. Chem. Mater. 29, 10037–10044 (2017)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR164" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2026">164</a></sup>, are expensive and not necessarily greener. High-concentration electrolytes (HCEs) and localized high-concentration electrolytes (LHCEs) have emerged as promising approaches, as they reduce the total solvent volume and improve electrochemical stability<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 165" title="He, M. et al. Realizing solid-phase reaction in Li–S batteries via localized high-concentration carbonate electrolyte. Adv. Energy Mater. 11, 2101004 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR165" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2030">165</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 166" title="Liu, J. et al. Localized high-concentration binary salt electrolytes with suppressed Li2S x solubility to achieve stable Li–S pouch cells with high sulfur-loading cathodes under lean electrolyte conditions. ACS Appl. Energy Mater. (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR166" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2033">166</a></sup>. Other efforts focus on non-flammable or flame-retardant solvents, including sulfone-, phosphate-, and ionic liquid-based formulations<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 167" title="Josef, E. et al. Ionic liquids and their polymers in lithium-sulfur batteries. Isr. J. Chem. 59, 832–842 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR167" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2037">167</a></sup>. Ultimately, aqueous-based electrolytes, which are suitable for applications prioritizing low cost and safety, such as large-scale energy storage, and SSEs, which are aimed at achieving high energy density, both eliminate organic solvents entirely and represent the most promising solutions for long-term environmental compatibility and safety, although each has its own limitations as discussed above.</p><p>The binder also presents environmental concerns. Polyvinylidene fluoride (PVDF) is widely used in both LIBs and LSBs due to its outstanding chemical and electrochemical stability. However, PVDF is a fluoropolymer containing highly stable carbon-fluorine bonds, making it persistent in the environment. Like per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS), PVDF is considered a “forever chemical”, contributing to long-term environmental pollution. Furthermore, PVDF is typically processed using NMP, which requires careful handling and expensive recovery systems. These processing demands increase health risks, production costs, and environmental footprint, particularly in industrial-scale battery manufacturing. PVDF also complicates battery recycling: it is difficult to separate from active materials, resistant to thermal decomposition, and incompatible with biodegradable or green recovery processes.</p><p>To overcome these limitations, several water-processable, environmentally friendly binders are being developed. For example, carboxymethyl cellulose (CMC) is a biodegradable binder commonly used in LFP cathodes and can be processed in aqueous solutions<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 168" title="Zhang, Z. et al. Cellulose-based material in lithium-sulfur batteries: A review. Carbohydr. Polym. 255, 117469 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR168" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2048">168</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 169" title="Chen, Z., Li, S., Zhang, G., Yang, Y. &amp; Qian, Y. Renewable lignocellulose based binders for advanced battery systems. Green. Chem. 26, 9993–10005 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR169" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2051">169</a></sup>. Other promising alternatives include polyacrylic acid (PAA), which provides strong adhesion and water compatibility, and biopolymer-based binders such as alginate, chitosan, and starch derivatives<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 170" title="Zalka, D. et al. Improving lithium-sulfur battery performance using a polysaccharide binder derived from red algae. Commun. Mater. 6, 17 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR170" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2055">170</a></sup>.</p><p>In the context of recycling, the path toward sustainability for SBBs remains complex<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 171" title="Schwich, L., Sabarny, P. &amp; Friedrich, B. Recycling potential of lithium–sulfur batteries—a first concept using thermal and hydrometallurgical methods. Metals 10, 1513 (2020)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR171" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2062">171</a></sup>. On the one hand, SBBs benefit from a low content of critical metals, apart from lithium in LSBs, which reduces their environmental footprint compared to cobalt- and nickel-rich LIBs. On the other hand, this scarcity of valuable metals also diminishes the economic incentive for recycling, as the recoverable material value is significantly lower. In fact, recycling LSBs is even less cost-effective than LIB recycling, which itself is only marginally viable when compared to the cost of raw material extraction through mining.</p><p>Nonetheless, SBBs offer several promising opportunities for circular material flows. LSBs can be produced from recycled lithium recovered from end-of-life LIBs, and the sulfur can be sourced from industrial waste streams, such as petroleum refining or low-cost pyrite mining, which has limited commercial value today due to the low market price of sulfur and iron<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 16" title="Huang, Y. C., Wu, C. C. &amp; Chung, S. H. Enhanced performance of lithium-sulfur batteries using construction wastes: a sustainable approach to high-loading sulfur cathodes. ChemSusChem 18, e202402206 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR16" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2069">16</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 172" title="Priyadarshi, R. et al. Sulfur recycling into value-added materials: a review. Environ. Chem. Lett. 21, 1673–1699 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR172" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2072">172</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 173" title="Grace, J. P., Kaliprasad, Y. &amp; Martha, S. K. Reduced graphene oxide derived from the spent graphite anodes as a sulfur host in lithium–sulfur batteries. Energy Adv. 4, 152–161 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR173" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2075">173</a></sup>. The transition metals used in small quantities as catalytic dopants (e.g., Fe, Co, Ni) may also be sourced from ferroalloy or steel by-products, provided that purity levels are sufficient<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 174" title="Bonilla, Á et al. Boosting Li-S batteries through the synergistic effect of recycled ferrites and external magnetic induction. J. Power Sources 628, 235856 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR174" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2079">174</a></sup>. In parallel, efforts are underway to produce conductive and porous carbon materials from biomass or polymer waste, further aligning SBBs with sustainable material sourcing<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 175" title="Zhou, Y., Zhang, Y. &amp; Li, X. Upcycling of paper waste for high-performance lithium-sulfur batteries. Mater. Today Energy 19, 100591 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR175" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2083">175</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 176" title="García-Soriano, F. J. et al. Biocarbon from olive pomace residue as a sulfur host for carbonate-based lithium-sulfur batteries. Commun. Mater. 6, 1–10 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR176" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2086">176</a></sup>.</p><p>However, to ensure long-term viability, it will be essential to understand how impurities in recycled or low-grade materials affect electrochemical performance, and to develop the required cost-effective purification strategies to meet battery-grade specifications. Only by integrating materials sustainability, safe and green processing, and innovative recycling pathways can SBBs fully realize their promise as a next-generation, environmentally friendly energy storage technology.</p><p>Overall, while it may be possible to address individual limitations of SBBs in isolation, the strong interdependence among various factors, such as electrochemical performance, material stability, manufacturing constraints, safety, and sustainability, makes holistic optimization of these systems extremely challenging (Fig.&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig11">11</a>). Improvements in one area often introduce trade-offs in others, underscoring the need for integrated, system-level design strategies to achieve practical and scalable sulfur-based battery technologies.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-11" data-title="Interconnected SBB limitations."><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig11" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 11: Interconnected SBB limitations.</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig11_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-11-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-11-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig11_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 11: Interconnected SBB limitations." loading="lazy" width="685" height="697"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-11-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/11" data-track-dest="link:Figure11 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 11" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-11-desc"><p>Schematic illustration of the key limitations affecting SBBs, along with some of the underlying mechanisms that drive these challenges. The diagram also presents a non-exhaustive set of potential mitigation strategies and their associated trade-offs, emphasizing the intricate interdependencies between different limitations and solution pathways. The € symbol highlights the need for investment.</p></div></div></figure></div></div></div></section><section data-title="Prospects for SBB manufacturing and commercialization"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec14-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec14">Prospects for SBB manufacturing and commercialization</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec14-content"><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec15">Commercialization pathways</h3><p>The scaling of SBBs from laboratory prototypes to industrial manufacturing encounters multifaceted challenges beyond core technological barriers. These include critical shortages in specialized manufacturing equipment, construction-grade materials, and a skilled workforce<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 144" title="Chen, S. et al. Active organic salts enabling non-intrusive electrolyte presodiation strategy. Adv. Mater. 37, 2502251 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR144" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2131">144</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 177" title="Jan, W., Khan, A. D., Iftikhar, F. J. &amp; Ali, G. Recent advancements and challenges in deploying lithium sulfur batteries as economical energy storage devices. J. Energy Storage 72, 108559 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR177" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2134">177</a></sup>. These supply-chain and talent constraints have contributed to significant production ramp-up delays across the emerging battery cell industry<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 178" title="Battery 2030. Battery 2030: Sustainable batteries of the future, 
                  https://battery2030.eu/
                  
                 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR178" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2138">178</a></sup>. Despite these hurdles, a clear trajectory toward commercial viability is materializing (see Fig.&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Fig12">12</a>), evidenced by substantial investment and accelerated strategic partnerships. The sector’s advancement is now being driven by a coalition of innovative startups and established industry leaders. Key players currently shaping the field include Anglo-Australian firm Gelion plc, LG Energy Solution (LGES), Germany-based Theion, Belgium’s Umicore, U.S.-based companies Lyten and Zeta Energy, the British firm StorTera, and Chinese entities such as General New Energy and Xiamen Tungsten Company, collectively signaling robust commercial momentum.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-12" data-title="Fig. 12"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig12" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 12</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><img aria-describedby="figure-12-desc ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-12-1" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs43246-026-01133-w/MediaObjects/43246_2026_1133_Fig12_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 12" loading="lazy" width="685" height="339"></picture><span class="u-visually-hidden" id="ai-alt-disclaimer-figure-12-1">The alt text for this image may have been generated using AI.</span><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/figures/12" data-track-dest="link:Figure12 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 12" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-12-desc"><p>Commercialization trajectories of SBBs.</p></div></div></figure></div><p>The commercialization of SBBs is fundamentally driven by the exceptionally high theoretical energy density of sulfur cathodes. This compelling value proposition has attracted significant investment from leading automotive and technology corporations, who are actively advancing SBB research and development to capitalize on their potential across diverse applications, from EVs to drones and portable electronics. Within the current industrial landscape, a clear strategic bifurcation has emerged as companies target specific market priorities. This is characterized by a pursuit of either Maximum Energy Density (as exemplified by firms like Li-S Energy) or Optimized Durability and Cycle Life (as seen with the approach of companies like Lyten). The latest benchmarks for these leading commercial pathways are detailed in Table&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Tab3">3</a>.</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-3"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab3" data-test="table-caption">Table 3 Current Performance Benchmarks for Leading Li-S Commercialization (c. 2024-2025)</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/tables/3" aria-label="Full size table 3"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec16">Failures, acquisitions, and R&amp;D&amp;I SBBs landscape</h3><p>The path to commercialization has not been without casualties, offering critical lessons for the industry. Oxis Energy, a UK-based pioneer in Li-S technology, served as a prominent early leader, achieving prototype cells with specific energies exceeding 470 Wh/kg and securing partnerships for electric aviation. Despite these technical milestones, the company faced insurmountable financial hurdles in scaling its production facilities, entering administration in May 2021<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 179" title="Electrive. Oxis Energy is facing bankruptcy, 
                  https://www.electrive.com/2021/05/21/oxis-energy-is-facing-bankruptcy/
                  
                 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR179" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2379">179</a></sup>. The dissolution of Oxis Energy highlights the “valley of death” between prototype success and industrial viability. However, its technology did not disappear; its extensive intellectual property (IP) portfolio was acquired by Johnson Matthey and subsequently sold to Gelion plc, ensuring that decades of manufacturing know-how continue to contribute to the sector’s advancement<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 180" title="Matthey, J. Johnson Matthey acquires assets to accelerate green hydrogen scale-up, 
                  https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/johnson-matthey-acquires-assets-to-accelerate-green-hydrogen-scale-up-301343268.html
                  
                 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR180" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2383">180</a></sup>.</p><p>Additionally, Gelion’s acquisition<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 181" title="Gelion. Strategic UK Acquisition and Expansion, 
                  https://gelion.com/news/strategic-uk-acquisition-and-expansion/
                  
                 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR181" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2390">181</a></sup> of UK-based Li-S specialist OXLiD in November 2023 has significantly strengthened its R&amp;D capabilities by integrating a team of experienced battery scientists, IP portfolio, and academic partnerships (Nottingham, Oxford, University College of London, Faraday Institution). This acquisition effectively combined Oxis’s historical manufacturing data with OXLiD’s advanced cathode formulations. It brings advanced cathode formulations and anode protection technologies, accelerating progress toward &gt;400 Wh/kg pouch cells and longer cycle life<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 182" title="Gelion. Gelion, 
                  https://gelion.com/
                  
                 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR182" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2394">182</a></sup>. Gelion also secured additional grant funding to support scaling. In 2025, it entered a strategic partnership with the Max Planck Institute (MPI) in Potsdam to co-develop high-power sulfur batteries using MPI’s nano-confined carbon/sulfur cathode and anode technologies, originally demonstrated in Na-S systems with 10 C rates and extended lifetimes<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 183" title="Gelion. Strategic Partnership with Max Planck Institute, 
                  https://gelion.com/news/strategic-partnership-max-planck-institute/
                  
                 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR183" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2398">183</a></sup>. Early Li-S tests show promise, and efforts are underway to scale from coin to pouch cells in both Na-S and Li-S formats. The collaboration includes joint IP development, with Gelion holding exclusive commercial rights aligned with its commercialization roadmap (Table&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Tab4">4</a>).</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-4"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab4" data-test="table-caption">Table 4 Key failure factors in SBB commercialization</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/tables/4" aria-label="Full size table 4"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p>Umicore, a leading supplier of battery materials, is advancing according to its Battery Materials Solutions roadmap through 2028<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 184" title="Umicore. Umicore unveils roadmap to 2028, 
                  https://www.umicore.com/en/media/newsroom/umicore-unveils-roadmap-to-2028/
                  
                 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR184" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2522">184</a></sup>, which emphasizes improvements in cathode material efficiency and cost control. However, despite its strong position in lithium-ion supply chains, Umicore’s investment in sulfur cathode R&amp;D is less transparent; no full-scale Li-S pilot project has been publicly disclosed to date, suggesting that Li-S remains a secondary focus.</p><p>Coherent has announced strategic initiatives centered on its LSB platform, built around its proprietary sulfur immobilization technology<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 185" title="Coherent. Strategic Alternatives for Its Lithium Sulfur Battery Platform, 
                  https://www.coherent.com/news/press-releases/review-of-strategic-altneratives-for-lithium-sulfur-battery-platform
                  
                 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR185" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2529">185</a></sup>. The company is currently evaluating options to advance the commercialization of this breakthrough system, which has received recognition and funding from the U.S. Department of Energy and IARPA.</p><p>Remarkable industrial developments are also taking place in China. For instance, General New Energy claims to offer LSBs an energy density exceeding 450 Wh/kg and a cycle life of 1500 cycles, enabling more than two hours of operation for unmanned aerial vehicles<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 186" title="GNE. General New Energy, 
                  https://www.gne-ls.com/
                  
                 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR186" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2537">186</a></sup>. Xiamen Tungsten Company has also achieved breakthroughs in the production of high-purity lithium sulfide, supporting the advancement of SSE systems and Li-Li₂S battery technologies<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 187" title="XTC. XTC New Energy, 
                  https://en.xtc-xny.com/
                  
                 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR187" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2541">187</a></sup>.</p><p>In parallel, liquid-sulfur systems for stationary energy storage have already reached the market. StorTera, for example, is commercializing a graphite-sulfur liquid flow battery designed for long-duration grid applications<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 188" title="Stortera. Stortera, 
                  https://www.stortera.com/
                  
                 (2020)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR188" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2548">188</a></sup>. Besides, high-temperature Na-S technology is gaining traction. BASF and Japan’s NGK Insulators have launched the NAS MODEL L24 grid-scale battery, achieving &lt;1% annual degradation and <span class="stix">∼</span>20% lower lifetime costs compared to previous models. BASF, as distributor and strategic partner, is accelerating deployment in Japan, the U.S., and Southeast Asia, leveraging its position in long-duration energy storage initiatives.</p><p>European R&amp;D initiatives have played a pivotal role in bridging lab-scale research with market deployment. For instance, the H2020 HELIS project, coordinated by the Kemijski Institut, aimed to advance LSBs toward commercialization<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 189" title="European Commission. Horizon 2020: High energy lithium sulphur cells and batteries. Report No. 666221, 
                  https://cordis.europa.eu/project/id/666221/reporting
                  
                 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR189" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2555">189</a></sup>. Similarly, the M-ERA.NET ALISA project, also led by the Kemijski Institut, focused on the development of LSBs using ultramicroporous carbons<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 190" title="M-ERA.NET. ALISA project - Advanced Lithium-Sulfur batteries with ultramicroporous carbons - ALISA,
                  https://www.m-era.net/materipedia/2021/alisa
                  
                 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR190" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2559">190</a></sup>. The H2020 SPIDER project, coordinated by CEA, targeted the development of high-energy-density batteries based on sulfur rocksalt cathodes<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 191" title="European Commission. Horizon 2020: Safe and prelithiated high energy Density batteries based on sulphur Rocksalt and silicon chemistries. Report No. 814389, 
                  https://cordis.europa.eu/project/id/814389/reporting
                  
                 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR191" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2563">191</a></sup>. The Horizon Europe Talissman project, coordinated by CIDETEC and currently underway, is working on next-generation technologies for advanced LSBs<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 192" title="Cordis. Technologies for Advanced Lithium-Sulfur batteries toward Safe and Sustainable Mobility Applications, 
                  https://cordis.europa.eu/project/id/101203047
                  
                 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR192" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2567">192</a></sup>. In parallel, the Horizon Europe HealingBat project, under the Battery2030+ initiative and coordinated by TU Dortmund, explores self-healing mechanisms in sulfur-based battery systems<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 193" title="Healing Bat. Healing Bat, 
                  https://www.healingbat.eu/
                  
                 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR193" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2571">193</a></sup>. Additionally, the ERA-MIN 3 2BoSS project, coordinated by IREC and completed in May 2025, has focused on demonstrating the integration of Li₂S cathodes, graphite-free silicon anodes, and biomass-derived nitrogen-doped carbon, contributing to enhanced circularity and sustainability<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 194" title="2BoSS. 2BoSS Project, 
                  https://2boss.eu
                  
                 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR194" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2576">194</a></sup>.</p><p>These initiatives illustrate how coordinated technological and industrial strategies are essential for overcoming scale-up barriers. By replacing critical raw materials such as cobalt and nickel with sulfur, SBBs offer compelling cost and environmental advantages. Advances in SSEs and functional additives are also addressing key challenges like dendrite formation and cycle life. As these technologies evolve, SBBs could revolutionize transportation and grid storage, supporting the global energy transition.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec17">Prospects for SBB manufacturing</h3><p>LSB commercialization should benefit from its seamless integration with existing LIB manufacturing infrastructure, lowering costs and accelerating scale-up. Founded in 2015, Lyten has emerged as a leader in LSB development through its proprietary 3D graphene materials platform. Lyten’s pilot line in San Jose, launched in May 2023, was implemented using standard LIB equipment and processes. It achieved operational status within six weeks and required less than 2% of the typical capital investment<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 195" title="Lyten. Lithium-Sulfur Batteries, 
                  https://lyten.com/products/lithium-sulfur-batteries
                  
                 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR195" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2591">195</a></sup>. This line maintains a consistent yield above 90%, underscoring not only compatibility but also a high level of manufacturing maturity. Furthermore, Lyten’s chemistry eliminates the need for NMP and other contamination-sensitive materials, simplifying processing and reducing cleaning requirements. This minimal disruption to existing gigafactory operations enables a smooth transition to LSBs through line retrofitting, rather than costly new construction, supporting rapid commercialization and strong unit economics.</p><p>To address environmental and safety concerns associated with volatile ether-based solvents like DOL and DME, the industry is shifting toward low-volatility alternatives such as glyme-based solvents (e.g., TEGDME), which offer improved thermal stability and reduced flammability. The industry is also exploring fluorine-free binders as replacements for PVDF, eliminating the need for toxic processing solvents. These innovations aim to reduce the environmental footprint of LSBs while enabling their integration into industrial-scale battery manufacturing. Collectively, these developments not only reduce the ecological and economic costs of LSBs but also accelerate their commercial readiness for applications in EVs, aerospace, and stationary storage.</p><p>Conventional LIB production relies on wet roll-to-roll (R2R) coating, where active materials are applied as solvent-based slurries using NMP. The subsequent drying phase is thermodynamically inefficient, as it requires massive industrial ovens to evaporate and recover solvents. This stage accounts for approximately 40% of a gigafactory’s total energy consumption and represents a significant bottleneck for scaling SBBs<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 196" title="Ahmed, S., Nelson, P. A., Gallagher, K. G. &amp; Dees, D. W. Energy impact of cathode drying and solvent recovery during lithium-ion battery manufacturing. J. Power Sources 322, 169–178 (2016)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR196" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2601">196</a></sup>. Incorporating solvent-free dry-electrode processing presents significant electrochemical and thermodynamic advantages for LSB manufacturing<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 197" title="Ludwig, B., Zheng, Z., Shou, W., Wang, Y. &amp; Pan, H. Solvent-free manufacturing of electrodes for lithium-ion batteries. Sci. Rep. 6, 23150 (2016)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR197" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2605">197</a></sup>. The high-shear forces employed in dry processing promote the fibrillation of PTFE binders, creating a three-dimensional “spider-web” matrix that provides superior mechanical anchoring for sulfur particles<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 198" title="Schumm, B. et al. Dry battery electrode technology: from early concepts to industrial applications. Adv. Energy Mater. 15, 2406011, 1–28 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR198" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2609">198</a></sup>. This uniform binder distribution, which eliminates the migration and surface segregation common in wet processing, is critical for maintaining electrode integrity during sulfur’s substantial volume expansion. From an electrochemical performance standpoint, the process enables the fabrication of thicker electrodes with higher mass loadings by removing the solvent-filled pores that typically require compression<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 199" title="Liang, Y. et al. Solvent-free bonding mechanisms and microstructure engineering in dry electrode technology for lithium-ion batteries. Adv. Funct. Mater. 36, e18619 1–32 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR199" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2613">199</a></sup>. This capability directly contributes to achieving higher gravimetric energy densities, targeting the 400–500 Wh/kg range required for applications like EVs, as demonstrated for LIBs<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 200" title="Liu, Y. et al. Toward scale-up of solid-state battery via dry electrode technology.  Energy 7, 100221 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR200" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2617">200</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 201" title="Sotomayor, M. E. et al. Ultra-thick battery electrodes for high gravimetric and volumetric energy density Li-ion batteries. J. Power Sources 437, 226923 (2019)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR201" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2620">201</a></sup>. However, a key challenge emerges: this inherent advantage of high density and low porosity can simultaneously hinder electrolyte infiltration and ionic transport in thick electrodes, as discussed in “Relatively high manufacturing costs and infrastructure compatibility”.</p><p>To resolve this, the successful application of dry processing for sulfur cathodes requires specific strategies to decouple densification from pore connectivity. One promising approach is the incorporation of sacrificial pore-forming agents (e.g., volatile solids, soluble salts, or depolymerizable additives) into the dry powder mix. These agents create controlled, interconnected void channels upon removal, ensuring adequate electrolyte infiltration without compromising the electrode’s structural integrity. Additionally, precise control over binder fibrillation is critical; by optimizing the shear intensity and mixing temperature, manufacturers can engineer a fine, fibrous PTFE network that provides cohesion without forming dense, ion-blocking films<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 202" title="Grabe, S. et al. Sulfur infiltration and allotrope formation in porous cathode hosts for lithium-sulfur batteries. AIChE J. 68, e17638 (2022)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR202" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2627">202</a></sup>. Furthermore, the use of mechanically robust, hierarchical carbon hosts (such as 3D graphene or carbon nanotubes) can resist pore collapse during high-pressure calendering, preserving the mesoporosity essential for accommodating sulfur’s volume expansion and facilitating rapid ion transport<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 203" title="Jerzy Gazda, B. L., Jeffrey Bell, David Cao, Prashanth JAMPANI HANUMANTHA, James McKinney, George Clayton Gibbs, Michael W. Stowell. Systems and methods of manufacture of carbon-based structures incorporated into lithium-ion and lithium sulfur (li s) battery electrodes. United States Patent (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR203" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2631">203</a></sup>.</p><p>A successful application of dry processing for sulfur cathodes requires the careful engineering of electrode architecture, striking a balance between the dense packing needed for energy density and the porous networks required for efficient ionic diffusion. Thermodynamically, the elimination of the solvent removal phase circumvents the latent heat of vaporization, leading to substantial operational energy savings. Economically, this translates to an estimated 15-20% reduction in operational expenditure (OPEX) and a capital expenditure (CAPEX) reduction of up to 30% through the elimination of extensive drying lines and solvent recovery systems<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 197" title="Ludwig, B., Zheng, Z., Shou, W., Wang, Y. &amp; Pan, H. Solvent-free manufacturing of electrodes for lithium-ion batteries. Sci. Rep. 6, 23150 (2016)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR197" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2639">197</a></sup>. Furthermore, the process aligns with stringent sustainability mandates by removing toxic, volatile organic compounds from the production chain, thereby reducing the environmental footprint of LSB manufacturing for high-volume markets.</p><p>Stellantis and Lyten are employing multiple strategies to reduce LSB production costs, including: (i) Alternative electrolytes, developing non-flammable, non-toxic solvents with wider electrochemical windows to improve safety and reduce handling costs; (ii) Cost-effective lithium salts, exploring cheaper alternatives to LiTFSI that do not compromise performance; (iii) Anode innovation, replacing lithium metal with silicon or modified graphite to simplify manufacturing; (iv) Process optimization, developing scalable, high-throughput production methods and robust supply chains for sulfur-based materials; (v) Simplified cell design, reducing reliance on additives and separator modifications to enhance cost competitiveness with LIBs.</p><p>To support scaling, Lyten has acquired Northvolt’s battery plant in San Leandro, California, and Dwa ESS operations in Gdańsk, Poland. In October 2024, it announced plans for a gigafactory in Nevada targeting 10 GWh of annual LSB production by 2027<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 204" title="Ni, W. Perspectives on Advanced Lithium–Sulfur Batteries for Electric Vehicles and Grid-Scale Energy Storage. Nanomaterials 14, 990 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR204" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2649">204</a></sup>. Stellantis has also invested in Lyten’s 3D graphene platform to improve energy density and cycling stability, aiming to address challenges such as sulfur’s low conductivity and cathode degradation during cycling<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 205" title="Stellantis. Stellantis Invests in Lyten’s Breakthrough Lithium-Sulfur EV Battery Technology, 
                  https://www.stellantis.com/en/news/press-releases/2023/may/stellantis-invests-in-lyten-s-breakthrough-lithium-sulfur-ev-battery-technology
                  
                 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR205" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2653">205</a></sup>. In parallel, Stellantis is collaborating with the French Alternative Energies and Atomic Energy Commission (CEA) to advance solid-state electrolytes and sulfur cathodes, with a focus on mitigating polysulfide dissolution and improving long-term stability.</p><p>Additionally, the industry is focusing on using abundant, low-cost feedstocks to further cut raw material costs. For example, Zeta Energy is developing sulfur cathodes from unrefined elemental sulfur and methane-derived carbon. These approaches aim to lower both environmental and economic costs, while meeting the performance needs of EVs. Collaborative efforts between battery developers and automotive manufacturers, targeting commercial-scale deployment by 2030, highlight the broader industry shift toward integrating next-generation chemistries into transportation platforms.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec18">Supply chain cost drivers for SBBs</h3><p>The commercial viability of SBBs hinges on achieving a compelling cost structure that can compete with or undercut established LIBs. By 2025, the commercial viability of SBBs is no longer a theoretical debate but a race against a rapidly falling price floor. To achieve true market penetration, SBBs must undercut a LIB industry that has reached record-low pack prices (Tables&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Tab5">5</a> and <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Tab6">6</a>). Driven by the industrial maturity of LFP supply chains, LIB costs have settled between $80 and $115 per kWh, depending on the chemistry. For SBBs to disrupt this status quo, they must aim for a target range of $65 to $90 per kWh - a feat that relies on offsetting expensive lithium-metal processing with the inherent cheapness of sulfur. The analysis identifies that while sulfur provides massive raw material savings, the lithium metal premium and electrolyte additives cost, and E/S ratio are the primary variables that will determine if SBBs can beat the $80/kWh benchmark of LFP batteries.</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-5"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab5" data-test="table-caption">Table 5 Comparison of the target cost of LSBs battery packs vs. leading LIB technologies</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/tables/5" aria-label="Full size table 5"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-6"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab6" data-test="table-caption">Table 6 Main SBB cost advantages and practical limitations</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/tables/6" aria-label="Full size table 6"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p>The primary challenge in constructing a definitive cost analysis for these technologies lies in their current status in the late-stage research and pilot-scale phase, with no standardized manufacturing processes or economies of scale established. While projections from academic and industry research point toward a promising economic pathway, this promise is tightly bound to overcoming significant material and engineering challenges. At first glance, the economic promise of the SBB is rooted in a paradox. Elemental sulfur is effectively a zero-cost material, a byproduct of oil refining available for pennies per kilogram. However, cost-modeling of the supply chain reveals that savings at the feedstock level are reclaimed by high-intensity upstream and midstream processing.</p><p>The primary cost bottleneck in the sulfur cathode supply chain is the synthesis of the conductive carbon host. Because sulfur is naturally insulating, it requires sophisticated frameworks like Lyten’s 3D Graphene™ or carbon nanotubes to facilitate electron transport. The high-temperature processing and chemical activation required to produce these high-surface-area hosts can account for up to 30% of the total cathode cost<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 206" title="Tian, J., Xing, F. &amp; Gao, Q. Graphene-based nanomaterials as the cathode for lithium-sulfur batteries. Molecules 26, 2507 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR206" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2899">206</a></sup>. Unlike the bulk sulfur itself, these engineered carbons require significant energy and specialized precursors, representing a “complexity tax” on the cathode.</p><p>While cell assembly (stacking and tab welding) represents a relatively small fraction of the total cost, the electrode fabrication stage is a major economic driver. Conventional slurry casting necessitates expensive solvent recovery and high-energy drying cycles to remove NMP. Furthermore, the narrative of cost-efficiency depends on active loading. To reach the competitive $70/kWh threshold, manufacturers must pack sulfur at high densities (exceeding 6 mAh/cm²). As Lu et al. demonstrated<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 207" title="Liu, J. et al. Design of size-controlled sulfur nanoparticle cathodes for lithium-sulfur aviation batteries. Small 19, 2300286 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR207" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e2906">207</a></sup>, failing to optimize the sulfur nanoparticle size during this fabrication step leads to hidden costs, requiring more current collectors and separators per pack to compensate for poor material utilization.</p><p>However, the most critical variable in the SBB cost equation is the anode. Moving from graphite to lithium metal introduces a processing premium that can erode, or even negate, the savings gained from sulfur. It is therefore important to distinguish the cost of lithium as a commodity from the cost of a battery-grade anode component. Bulk lithium metal ingots may trade on the order of <span class="stix">∼</span>$60–$80 kg⁻¹, implying a manageable raw-material contribution (<span class="stix">∼</span>$15 kWh⁻¹). However, SBBs do not use ingots; they require ultra-thin (&lt;50 µm), wide-width foils. Converting a sticky, highly reactive metal into uniform, battery-grade foil requires specialized forming and handling steps that drive a much larger effective price, with research- and pilot-scale foils commonly quoted at several hundred dollars per kilogram. This sensitivity is captured in Table <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Tab7">7</a>, which maps lithium-foil pricing onto final pack cost and identifies a clear “evaporation point” where the sulfur cost advantage disappears.</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-7"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab7" data-test="table-caption">Table 7 Sensitivity analysis of the impact of lithium foil pricing on the final pack cost</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/tables/7" aria-label="Full size table 7"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p>As illustrated, if production relies on conventional multi-pass rolling routes that keep foil costs above <span class="stix">∼</span>$150 kg⁻¹, the cost advantage of sulfur largely vanishes; at <span class="stix">∼</span>$200 kg⁻¹, the anode can dominate the allowable cost budget. Accordingly, the commercial viability of SBBs depends less on lowering the commodity price of lithium and more on manufacturing innovation, particularly scalable routes to wide-width, thin foils (e.g., melt-based continuous casting/melt-spinning concepts or direct deposition approaches such as physical vapor deposition) that can bypass the most costly rolling and finishing steps.</p><p>For sulfur-equivalent configurations that use Li₂S as the starting material (e.g., some solid-state variants and Li-free anode designs), Li₂S introduces an additional, moderate cost driver: beyond precursor costs, the synthesis and stringent handling required to achieve high purity typically make Li₂S substantially more expensive than elemental sulfur.</p><p>Lithium-metal processing also shifts cost into the manufacturing environment. Because lithium is highly reactive, production generally requires very dry, tightly controlled atmospheres, increasing both capital costs (dry-room infrastructure, sealing, and handling) and operating costs (continuous dehumidification and HVAC load). These factory-level penalties can be material at scale and should be treated as a separate lever, alongside the foil manufacturing route, when assessing SBB pack economics<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 3" title="Battery Report. (Volta Foundation, 2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR3" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3103">3</a></sup>.</p><p>The electrolyte represents the third pillar of the SBB cost challenge. Current modeling suggests that LSBs only achieve economic parity if they operate under a lean regime, meaning E/S must be kept below 3 μL/mg<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 208" title="Wang, G., Luo, X., Sun, W. &amp; Cai, J. Assessing the practical feasibility of solid-state lithium–sulfur batteries. Commun. Mater. 6, 211 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR208" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3110">208</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 209" title="Li, Z. et al. A three-way electrolyte with ternary solvents for high-energy-density and long-cycling lithium–sulfur pouch cells. SusMat 4, e191 (2024)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR209" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3113">209</a></sup>. The problem is twofold: first, the ether-based electrolytes required for high performance are significantly more expensive than standard LIB carbonates<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 210" title="Liu, G., Sun, Q., Li, Q., Zhang, J. &amp; Ming, J. Electrolyte issues in lithium–sulfur batteries: development, prospect, and challenges. Energy Fuels 35, 10405–10427 (2021)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR210" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3117">210</a></sup>. Second, operating with minimal liquid increases internal resistance. To counter this, manufacturers must use expensive additives to prevent premature failure. As Bresser et al. point out<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 211" title="Bresser, D., Passerini, S. &amp; Scrosati, B. Recent progress and remaining challenges in sulfur-based lithium secondary batteries–a review. Chem. Commun. 49, 10545–10562 (2013)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR211" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3121">211</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 212" title="Cleaver, T., Kovacik, P., Marinescu, M., Zhang, T. &amp; Offer, G. Perspective—commercializing lithium sulfur batteries: are we doing the right research?. J. Electrochem. Soc. 165, A6029 (2017)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR212" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3124">212</a></sup>, the industry is currently caught in a trade-off where using too much electrolyte to ensure reliability inadvertently kills the energy density and cost advantages that the technology was built to provide.</p><p>Despite these hurdles, two manufacturing “de-riskers” are currently paving the way for scale. The first is dry-electrode coating. By eliminating the solvent-slurry process used in traditional LIB production, the need for massive, energy-hungry drying ovens is removed. This single innovation can reduce a factory’s footprint by 50% and lower initial plant investment by 30%<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 200" title="Liu, Y. et al. Toward scale-up of solid-state battery via dry electrode technology.  Energy 7, 100221 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR200" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3131">200</a></sup>.</p><p>The second is the strategy of LIB line retrofitting. As we have seen in the previous section, learning from early pioneers like OXIS Energy, modern firms like Lyten are designing their cells to be compatible with 98% of existing LIB infrastructure. By utilizing standard pouch-cell stacking and calendaring, the barrier to entry is lowered from a multi-billion-dollar “ground-up” build to a strategic equipment upgrade<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 205" title="Stellantis. Stellantis Invests in Lyten’s Breakthrough Lithium-Sulfur EV Battery Technology, 
                  https://www.stellantis.com/en/news/press-releases/2023/may/stellantis-invests-in-lyten-s-breakthrough-lithium-sulfur-ev-battery-technology
                  
                 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR205" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3139">205</a></sup>.</p><p>In conclusion, the path to a $70/kWh SBB is technically visible but remains a high-stakes tightrope walk. The analysis confirms that the inherent low cost of sulfur is only a commercial reality if two conditions are met: (1) electrolyte consumption is minimized to lean regimes (&lt;3 μL/mg), and (2) lithium foil processing costs are slashed by &gt;70% through novel extrusion or deposition techniques. The inherent low cost of sulfur is only a commercial reality if it is paired with lean electrolyte operation and the adoption of solvent-free manufacturing. Without these engineering milestones, the SBB remains a laboratory curiosity; with them, it represents a viable successor to the LIB throne.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec19">Real-world application maturity</h3><p>The commercial adoption of SBBs is strategically positioned to target specific markets where their high gravimetric energy density offers a critical advantage over LIBs, particularly in applications where weight is paramount, even if their cycle life is currently more limited. This fundamental trade-off positions SBBs not as a wholesale replacement for LIBs, but as a complementary technology that serves specific, high-value niches.</p><p>Aviation and aerospace represent primary, immediate markets where the weight savings of SBBs are transformative. SBBs are enabling electric or hybrid aircraft for short-to-medium-haul routes and advanced unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs)<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 9" title="Hwang, J.-Y., Park, H., Kim, H., Kansara, S. &amp; Sun, Y.-K. Advanced Cathodes for Practical Lithium–Sulfur Batteries. Acc. Mater. Res. 6, 245–258 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR9" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3158">9</a></sup>. A compelling demonstration was achieved by LG Energy Solution in partnership with the Korea Aerospace Research Institute (KARI), which successfully flight-tested a Li-S battery-powered High Altitude Pseudo-Satellite (HAPS). The aircraft operated for 13 hours in the stratosphere, with 7 hours of stable flight under extreme conditions (−70 °C, near-vacuum pressure), powered by cells with 1.5-2 times the energy density of comparable LIBs<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 9" title="Hwang, J.-Y., Park, H., Kim, H., Kansara, S. &amp; Sun, Y.-K. Advanced Cathodes for Practical Lithium–Sulfur Batteries. Acc. Mater. Res. 6, 245–258 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR9" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3162">9</a></sup>. Similarly, companies like Lyten target up to 8 hours of drone flight time and have demonstrated over 3000 cycles for satellite applications<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 213" title="Lyten. Lyten, 
                  https://lyten.com/
                  
                 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR213" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3166">213</a></sup>, far exceeding the 300–500 cycles typical for current drone LIBs. As Table&nbsp;<a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#Tab8">8</a> illustrates, this performance is intrinsically linked to cathode engineering, where optimizing parameters like sulfur nanoparticle size in practical pouch cells yields exponential gains in aerial performance.</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-8"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab8" data-test="table-caption">Table 8 Performance metrics from Li-S pouch cells in drone flight assessment<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 13" title="Heo, J. et al. Recent advances in achieving high energy/power density of lithium–sulfur batteries for current and near-future applications. Battery Energy 4, e20240051 (2025)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR13" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3183">13</a></sup></b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w/tables/8" aria-label="Full size table 8"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p>EVs constitute another critical sector, where the push for longer driving ranges is driving interest in SBBs. The high energy density of sulfur cathodes could enable EVs to achieve ranges nearing 300 miles per charge, coupled with a cost advantage from the use of abundant sulfur<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 214" title="Castillo, J. et al. High Energy Density Lithium–Sulfur Batteries Based on Carbonaceous Two-Dimensional Additive Cathodes. ACS Appl. Energy Mater. 6, 3579–3589 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR214" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3324">214</a></sup>.</p><p>Grid Energy Storage presents a massive long-term opportunity, with global capacity projected to increase sixfold by 2030. SBBs are being explored as a potential low-cost, high-performance solution for large-scale storage, crucial for integrating renewables and ensuring grid stability<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 215" title="IEA. Batteries and Secure Energy Transitions. (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR215" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3331">215</a></sup>. However, a significant gap remains in cycle life - industrial-grade LIBs for grid storage typically achieve 2000–5000 cycles, far exceeding the 300–500 cycles common for current LSBs<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 216" title="Ohrelius, M., Berg, M., Wreland Lindström, R. &amp; Lindbergh, G. Lifetime limitations in multi-service battery energy storage systems. Energies 16, 3003 (2023)." href="/articles/s43246-026-01133-w#ref-CR216" id="ref-link-section-d281700530e3335">216</a></sup>. While this limits immediate adoption for long-duration applications requiring thousands of cycles over decades, it establishes a clear performance benchmark. Continued research into self-healing mechanisms and solid-state electrolytes is essential to bridge this durability gap and unlock the full potential of SBBs for the grid storage market.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Outlook"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec20-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec20">Outlook</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec20-content"><p>To enable SBBs to evolve from a promising research concept into a commercially viable energy storage technology, a comprehensive and strategic development roadmap is essential. As the automotive industry accelerates its shift toward electrification, the successful adoption of next-generation battery systems such as SBBs will depend on targeted technological innovations, robust industrial partnerships, and investments in scalable manufacturing infrastructure. A key element of this transition involves tailoring SBB products to meet the specific demands of different market segments. For instance, maximizing energy density will be critical for EVs, while cost-effectiveness and long service life will be paramount for stationary storage applications. Customizing battery configurations to align with these diverse application requirements will be essential to accelerate market adoption.</p><p>Early deployment, combined with rigorous performance testing across various use cases, will be crucial to building confidence and ensuring that SBBs meet commercial reliability standards. Strategic collaborations among industry, research institutions, and policymakers will be instrumental in addressing technical and scalability barriers. In parallel, investments in specialized manufacturing processes and resilient supply chains will support long-term growth. Reducing production costs through process optimization and component simplification will be vital for enhancing market competitiveness. Additionally, coordinated policy support, through subsidies, regulatory frameworks, and sustained research funding, can play a decisive role in accelerating the commercialization of SBB technologies.</p><p>From a technological standpoint, overcoming current limitations will require continued advances in cathode engineering (including the integration of conductive hosts, catalytic additives, and polysulfide-trapping architectures), electrolyte development (especially stable, higher ionic conductivity and lower viscosity formulations incorporating proper additives), and protective strategies for anodes (ranging from coatings to alternative materials). Recent progress in SBB cathode design has already addressed some of the core issues, such as the low conductivity of sulfur, its sluggish redox kinetics, and its large volume expansion during cycling, but further optimization is needed to enable high sulfur loadings, long cycle life, and consistent performance under practical conditions.</p><p>In particular, realizing the full potential of SBBs will require the development of multifunctional materials that improve redox kinetics, enhance interfacial stability, and support reversible sulfur conversion under ultra-lean electrolyte conditions. This includes advanced conductive matrices, selective redox mediators, robust artificial SEIs, and adaptive electrode architectures capable of withstanding mechanical and chemical stresses. Scalable and cost-effective manufacturing techniques will also be critical to translating laboratory-scale materials into viable commercial products. Moreover, emerging strategies such as self-healing binders and dynamic electrolyte systems show promise in extending battery lifespan and reliability.</p><p>However, when assessing the future development of SBBs, it is essential to align research with realistic laboratory and industrial constraints. Several common experimental parameters are impractical for commercial scale-up, including but not limited to the following: i) Cathode loading and thickness: While low-loading, thin cathodes simplify laboratory research, they fail to deliver the areal capacity and energy density required for practical applications. Industrial cells demand high-loading, thick electrodes that introduce significant mechanical and transport challenges absent from typical lab studies. ii) E/S ratio: Excess electrolyte is frequently used to lower resistance and extend cycle life in experiments, but it inflates cost, weight, and reduces volumetric energy density, making it unacceptable for commercial cells, which must operate under lean-electrolyte conditions. iii) Non-scalable materials and designs: Strategies reliant on rare and expensive additives, low-conductivity 3D substrates, or structurally unstable cathodes often cannot be translated to the large-area, robust formats needed for manufacturing. iv) Pressure requirements for SSEs: Although SSEs can enhance safety and suppress polysulfide shuttling, many ceramic or sulfide-based variants require impractically high stack pressures to maintain interfacial contact in large-format cells. Therefore, future SBB development must prioritize SSE designs that function under low or zero external pressure, employ scalable fabrication methods, and are validated under industrially relevant testing conditions.</p><p>Ultimately, the transition from fundamental research to commercial deployment will require a multidisciplinary approach that bridges materials science, electrochemical engineering, and system-level design. By aligning technological development with end-user needs and scalable manufacturing practices, SBBs have the potential to become a cornerstone of next-generation energy storage, offering a sustainable, high-performance alternative to conventional LIB technologies.</p></div></div></section>
                    
                </div>
            

